 = Vulture With Honor\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward \n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = [[David Nichtern]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = A When his simulator malfunctions, Clancy is forced to face a few real-world problems. Later, he meets a meditation master. \n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 7\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n| Title           = Turtles of the Eclipse\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward\n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = [[Caitlin Doughty]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = A boring trip takes a remarkable turn when Clancy accidentally falls into another world - and comes face to face with Death.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 8\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n| Title           = Mouse of Silver\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward\n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = Deneen Feding\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = Clancy joins his mother on an emotional journey through the wondrous cycle of birth, life and death.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Concept and creation===\nDuring the start of his podcast broadcast, Trussel received an email from Ward praising him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/netflix-the-midnight-gospel-release-date-trailer-adventure-time|title=Netflix's The Midnight Gospel: Exclusive First Look at Adventure Time Creator's Adult Animated Series - IGN|via=www.ign.com}}</ref> Some time later the two became friends and Ward suggested to Trussel to turn his podcast into an animated series. According to Ward, Trussel had the ability to make 2 hours of a meditation conversation funny.\nWard used a podcast between Trussel and Dr. Drew to create a proof of concept for the show with the two battling zombies. Later, the proof of concept ended up being incorporated into the pilot of the series. The two took the concept of the series in pitching form to Mike Moon, head of adult animations at Netflix. After gaining the green light, the two gathered a team of comedians and writers to start working on animation. The two assembled a team of approximately 190 people at Titmouse and started working on creating the episodes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/streaming/light-at-the-end-of-the-apocalypse-pen-ward-duncan-trussell-preach-the-midnight-gospel/|title=Light at the End of the Apocalypse: Pen Ward & Duncan Trussell Preach 'The Midnight Gospel'|first=Ramin|last=Zahed|date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\nMike Mayfield joined the project as supervising director.\nIn 2019, Netflix has ordered eight episodes, which is slated to premiere in sometime in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/netflix-order-adult-animated-series-the-midnight-gospel-from-pendleton-ward-duncan-trussell-1202814276/|title=Netflix Orders Adult Animated Series \u2018The Midnight Gospel\u2019 From Pendleton Ward & Duncan Trussell|first1=Denise|last1=Petski|first2=Denise|last2=Petski|date=December 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nThe first teaser was released on March 16, and the main trailer on April 6. \n\n==Release==\nThe eight-episode first season, ordered by Netflix, was released on April 20, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/04/the-midnight-gospel-review-1202224481/|title=\u2018The Midnight Gospel\u2019 Review: \u2018Adventure Time\u2019 Creator\u2019s Astonishing New Netflix Show|first1=Eric|last1=Kohn|first2=Eric|last2=Kohn|date=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|11639414}}\n\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Midnight Gospel}}\n[[Category:2020 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2020s animated television series]]\n[[Category:American adult animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Surrealist television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Netflix Animation]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Pendleton Ward]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Midnight Gospel\n| image                    = File:The Midnight Gospel promotional poster.jpg\n| caption                  = Promotional poster\n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Adult animation]]\n* [[Dark comedy]]\n* [[Science fantasy]]\n* [[Adventure fiction|Adventure]]\n* [[Interview]]\n}}\n| director                 = Pendleton Ward\n| creator                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Pendleton Ward]]\n* [[Duncan Trussell]]\n}}\n| voices                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Duncan Trussell\n* [[Phil Hendrie]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = [[Joe Wong (musician)|Joe Wong]]\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1\n| num_episodes             = 8\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Pendleton Ward\n* Duncan Trussell\n* Antonio Canobbio\n* Ben Kalina\n* Chris Prynoski\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Shannon Prynoski\n* Tony Salama\n}}\n| editor                   = Megan Love\n| cinematography           = \n| runtime                  = 20-36 minutes\n| company                  = [[Titmouse, Inc.]]\n| distributor              = \n| channel                  = [[Netflix]]\n| picture_format           = [[4K resolution|4K]] ([[Ultra-high-definition television|Ultra HD]])<br>[[High-dynamic-range video|High dynamic range]]\n| audio_format             = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2020|4|20}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| website                  = https://www.netflix.com/title/80987903\n}}\n\n'''''The Midnight Gospel''''' is an [[American]] [[adult animated]] web television series created by ''[[Adventure Time]]''{{'s}} [[Pendleton Ward]] and comedian [[Duncan Trussell]]. It is the first animated production from Ward for [[Netflix]]. Set in Chromatic Ribbon, a spacecaster named Clancy owns a illegal multiverse simulator. Through it, he travels through worlds about to have their own apocalypses interviewing some of their residents for their spacecast.<ref>https://bleedingcool.com/tv/the-midnight-gospel-transmits-countdown-clock-from-chromatic-ribbon/</ref> The show features special guests like [[Phil Hendrie]], [[Stephen Root]], [[Drew Pinsky]], Trudy Goodman, Jason Louv, [[Caitlin Doughty]], [[Damien Echols]], [[David Nichtern]], and Deneen Fendig.\n\nThe show debuted on April 20, 2020 on Netflix.\n\n==Synopsis==\n''The Midnight Gospel'' revolves around a spacecaster{{what?}} named Clancy as he travels through cosmic realms and dimensions, interviewing the living creatures inside his malfunctioning multiverse simulator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/streaming/netflix-nabs-new-show-from-adventure-time-creator-pen-ward/|title=Netflix Nabs New Show from 'Adventure Time' Creator Pen Ward|first=Ramin|last=Zahed|date=December 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nerdist.com/article/the-midnight-gospel-trailer/|title=The Midnight Gospel Looks Like a Trippier ADVENTURE TIME|website=Nerdist}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/3/16/21181860/the-midnight-gospel-netflix-adventure-time-release-date-trailer|title=Trailer for Adventure Time creator's latest is a delightfully weird romp through the multiverse|first=Petrana|last=Radulovic|date=March 16, 2020|website=Polygon}}</ref>\n\n==Cast and characters==\n===Main===\n* [[Duncan Trussell]] as Clancy\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Phil Hendrie]] as Universe Simulator and various characters\n* [[Stephen Root]] as Bill Taft and various characters\n* [[Maria Bamford]] as Butt Demon and various characters\n* [[Doug Lussenhop]] as Daniel Hoops and various characters\n* [[Joey Diaz|Joey \"Coco\" Diaz]] as Chuck Charles and various characters\n* [[Christina Pazsitzky|Christina P.]] as Bobua and various characters\n* [[Steve Little (actor)|Steve Little]] as Captain Bryce and various characters\n* [[Johnny Pemberton]] as various characters\n\n===Guest stars===\n* [[Drew Pinsky]] as Little President (Episode 1 and Episode 5)\n* Anne Lammot as Anne Deer Dog (Episode 2)\n* Raghu Markas as Raghu Deer Dog (Episode 2)\n* [[Damien Echols]] as Darryl the Fish (Episode 3)\n* Trudy Goodman as Trudy the Love Barbarian (Episode 4)\n* Jason Louv as Jason (Episode 5)\n* [[David Nichtern]] as His Divine Grace, God's Scientist (Episode 1) and David (Episode 6)\n* [[Caitlin Doughty]] as Death (Episode 7)\n* Deneen Feding as herself aka Duncan's mom and Clancy's mom (Episode 8)\n* [[Ram Dass]] as Ram Dass (Episode 8)\n\n==Episodes==\n===Season 1 (2020)===\n{{Episode table |background=#FEDA4A |overall=5 |season=5 |title=26 |director=12 |writer=35 |aux2=14 |airdate=17 |aux2T=Interview Subject(s) |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = Taste of the King\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward\n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = [[Drew Pinsky]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = Clancy visits Earth 4-169, which happens to be in the midst of a zombie apocalypse. Clancy decides to interview the sim Glasses Man, who he discovers is, in fact, the President in this universe. In front of the White House, a group of anti-marijuana protesters are gathered, seemingly unbothered by the zombies around them. This sparks debate between Clancy and Glasses Man as to whether there is such a thing as a 'good drug' or a 'bad drug'. Over the course of the episode, the two discuss the pros and cons of psychedelics, the dangers of drug usage if not well educated, and whether or not drugs can be beneficial for an individual's personal spiritual growth.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = Officers and Wolves\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward \n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell, Brendon Walsh and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = Anne Lammot and Raghu Markas\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = On a planet populated by baby clowns, Clancy hears a deer-dog's thoughts on death as they head to a slaughterhouse.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           = Hunters Without a Home\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward\n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n|Aux2             = [[Damien Echols]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = Clancy zaps to an underwater planet, where he crosses paths with Darryl, a student of ceremonial magic and the path to enlightenment. \n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = Blinded by my End\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward \n| WrittenBy       = Meredith Kecskemety, Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = Trudy Goodman\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = A mishap sends Clancy to a medieval planet, where he rides along with a knight on a mission to avenge her lover's murder.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| Title           = Annihilation of Joy\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward \n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = Jason Louv\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = At a prison for simulated beings suffering from existential dread, Clancy ponders reality as he watches an inmate perish over and over.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 6\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n| Title           = Vulture With Honor\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward \n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = [[David Nichtern]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = A When his simulator malfunctions, Clancy is forced to face a few real-world problems. Later, he meets a meditation master. \n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 7\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n| Title           = Turtles of the Eclipse\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward\n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = [[Caitlin Doughty]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = A boring trip takes a remarkable turn when Clancy accidentally falls into another world - and comes face to face with Death.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 8\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n| Title           = Mouse of Silver\n| DirectedBy      = Pendleton Ward\n| WrittenBy       = Mike L. Mayfield, Duncan Trussell and Pendleton Ward\n| Aux2            = Deneen Feding\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|04|20}}\n| ShortSummary    = Clancy joins his mother on an emotional journey through the wondrous cycle of birth, life and death.\n| LineColor       = FEDA4A\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Concept and creation===\nDuring the start of his podcast broadcast (around 2013), Trussel received an email from Ward praising him for his podcast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/netflix-the-midnight-gospel-release-date-trailer-adventure-time|title=Netflix's The Midnight Gospel: Exclusive First Look at Adventure Time Creator's Adult Animated Series - IGN|via=www.ign.com}}</ref> About a year later, Ward left Adventure Time. <ref>https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-news/adventure-time-the-trippiest-show-on-television-84180/</ref> Despite saying in an interview that he would not work on another series, Ward was taking the first steps in a new series anchored in the adaptation of Trussell's podcast. Some time later Trussell and Ward became friends and Ward suggested to Trussell to turn his podcast into an animated series. According to Ward, Trussel had the ability to make 2 hours of a meditation conversation funny. Trussell says: \"He reached out to me and said he had an idea for how to animate my podcast, which was another big thrill for me.\" <ref>https://www.inverse.com/entertainment/midnight-gospel-netflix-duncan-trussell-pendleton-ward</ref> In the fist meeting with Ward, Trussell declined to join to a new project claiming he was too busy to turn his podcast into a animated show. In 2018, Ward approached to him again to show a rough concept taking a podcast conversation about drug addiction and playing it over an animatronic of Trussell and his guest fighting off a zombie invasion. <ref>https://www.inverse.com/entertainment/midnight-gospel-netflix-duncan-trussell-pendleton-ward</ref>\nLater, the rough of concept ended up being incorporated into the pilot of the serie. The two took the concept of the series in pitching form to Mike Moon, head of adult animations at Netflix. In 2019, Netflix has ordered eight episodes, which is slated to premiere in sometime in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/netflix-order-adult-animated-series-the-midnight-gospel-from-pendleton-ward-duncan-trussell-1202814276/|title=Netflix Orders Adult Animated Series \u2018The Midnight Gospel\u2019 From Pendleton Ward & Duncan Trussell|first1=Denise|last1=Petski|first2=Denise|last2=Petski|date=December 20, 2019}}</ref> After gaining the green light, the two gathered a team of comedians like Johnny Pemberton, Brendon Walsh, Weird Al Yankovic and Emo Philips were joined by occult scholar Jason Louv and white witch Maja D\u2019Aoust. The two assembled a team of approximately 190 people at Titmouse and started working on creating the episodes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/streaming/light-at-the-end-of-the-apocalypse-pen-ward-duncan-trussell-preach-the-midnight-gospel/|title=Light at the End of the Apocalypse: Pen Ward & Duncan Trussell Preach 'The Midnight Gospel'|first=Ramin|last=Zahed|date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\nMike Mayfield joined the project as supervising director and write for all the episodes. The team behind the show are composed by Jesse Moynihan (art director), Antonio Canobbio (Chief Creative Officer for Titmouse), Mike Roush (animation director) and Joey Adams (storyboard supervisor). Mayfield said that the time needed to \"try something nine different ways before one little change would make it go from clunky to incredible.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/streaming/light-at-the-end-of-the-apocalypse-pen-ward-duncan-trussell-preach-the-midnight-gospel/|title=Light at the End of the Apocalypse: Pen Ward & Duncan Trussell Preach 'The Midnight Gospel'|first=Ramin|last=Zahed|date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\nFor Ward, the new serie was a chance to explore the brave, new world of making animation for grown-ups. Until then he had made animations for children only and the new show would be a chance to change his way of making animations using the ultra-violence of cartoons with conversations on compassion. Ward also allowed Trussell to include his own original music in several episodes. The show's title came from the good news sense of the word gospel.Trussell says \"\u2019Gospel\u2019 means good news, and I was hoping that we convey the message that even through the most catastrophic situations, when everything is falling part, there is opportunity to grow as a person,\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/streaming/light-at-the-end-of-the-apocalypse-pen-ward-duncan-trussell-preach-the-midnight-gospel/|title=Light at the End of the Apocalypse: Pen Ward & Duncan Trussell Preach 'The Midnight Gospel'|first=Ramin|last=Zahed|date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n===Marketing===\nThe first teaser was released on March 16, and the main trailer on April 6. \n\n==Release==\nThe eight-episode first season, ordered by Netflix, was released on April 20, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/04/the-midnight-gospel-review-1202224481/|title=\u2018The Midnight Gospel\u2019 Review: \u2018Adventure Time\u2019 Creator\u2019s Astonishing New Netflix Show|first1=Eric|last1=Kohn|first2=Eric|last2=Kohn|date=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|11639414}}\n\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Midnight Gospel}}\n[[Category:2020 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2020s animated television series]]\n[[Category:American adult animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Surrealist television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Netflix Animation]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Pendleton Ward]]\n", "name_user": "Prince Silversaddle", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Midnight_Gospel"}
{"title_page": "Scotland national football team", "text_new": "{{short description|Men's association football team representing Scotland}}\n{{About|the men's team|the women's team|Scotland women's national football team}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox national football team\n| Name               = Scotland\n| Badge              = Scotland national football team logo 2014.svg\n| Badge_size         = 180px\n| FIFA Trigramme     = SCO\n| Association        = [[Scottish Football Association]]\n| Confederation      = [[UEFA]] (Europe)\n| Coach              = [[Steve Clarke]]\n| Captain            = [[Andrew Robertson]]\n| Most caps          = [[Kenny Dalglish]] (102)\n| Top scorer         = [[Kenny Dalglish]]<br/>[[Denis Law]] (30)\n| Home Stadium       = [[Hampden Park]]\n| FIFA Rank          = {{FIFA World Rankings|SCO}}\n| FIFA max           = 13<ref name=\"peak ranking\">{{cite news| title=Scots close in on England ranking | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7059726.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |work= |date=24 October 2007 | accessdate=14 October 2015}}</ref>\n| FIFA max date      = October 2007\n| FIFA min           = 88<ref>{{cite news| title=Wales fall in Fifa world rankings | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4377609.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |work= | date=24 March 2005 | accessdate=13 May 2007}}</ref>\n| FIFA min date      = March 2005\n| Elo Rank           = {{World Football Elo Ratings|Scotland}}\n| Elo max            = 1<ref name=\"World Football Elo Ratings\"/>\n| Elo max date       = 1876\u201392, 1904\n| Elo min            = 64<ref name=\"World Football Elo Ratings\"/>\n| Elo min date       = May 2005\n| pattern_la1        = _sco20h\n| pattern_b1         = _sco20h\n| pattern_ra1        = _sco20h\n| pattern_sh1        = _adidas_white\n| pattern_so1        = _3_stripes_white\n| leftarm1           = 05005B\n| body1              = 05005B\n| rightarm1          = 05005B\n| shorts1            = 000055\n| socks1             = 000055\n| pattern_la2        = _sco20a\n| pattern_b2         = _sco20a\n| pattern_ra2        = _sco20a\n| pattern_sh2        = _sco16h\n| pattern_so2        = _3_stripes_navy\n| leftarm2           = FFFF4A\n| body2              = FFFF4A\n| rightarm2          = FFFF4A\n| shorts2            = \n| socks2             = FFFFFF\n| First game         = {{fb|SCO|1542}} [[1872 Scotland v England football match|0\u20130]] {{fb-rt|ENG}}<br />([[Partick]], Scotland; 30 November 1872)\n| Largest win        = {{fb|SCO|1542}}  11\u20130 {{Fb-rt|IRE|1783}}<br />([[Glasgow]], Scotland; 23 February 1901)\n| Largest loss       = {{Fb|URU}} 7\u20130 {{fb-rt|SCO|1542}}<br />([[Basel]], Switzerland; 19 June 1954)\n| World cup apps     = 8\n| World cup first    = 1954\n| World cup best     = [[1974 FIFA World Cup#FIFA Retrospective Ranking|9th, 1974]]\n| Regional name      = [[UEFA European Championship|European Championship]]\n| Regional cup apps  = 2\n| Regional cup first = [[UEFA Euro 1992|1992]]\n| Regional cup best  = Group stage ([[UEFA Euro 1992|1992]], [[UEFA Euro 1996|1996]])\n}}\n\nThe '''Scotland national football team''' represents [[Scotland]] in men's international [[association football|football]] and is controlled by the [[Scottish Football Association]]. It competes in the three major professional tournaments, the [[FIFA World Cup]], [[UEFA Nations League]] and the [[UEFA European Championship]]. Scotland, as a [[Countries of the United Kingdom|country of the United Kingdom]], is not a member of the [[International Olympic Committee]] and therefore the national team does not compete in the [[Olympic Games]]. The majority of [[Scotland national football team home stadium|Scotland's home matches]] are played at the national stadium, [[Hampden Park]].\n\nScotland is the joint oldest national football team in the world, alongside [[England national football team|England]], whom they played in the world's [[1872 Scotland v England football match|first international football match]] in [[1872 in sports|1872]]. Scotland has a long-standing [[England\u2013Scotland football rivalry|rivalry with England]],<ref name=\"them\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/special_report/1999/11/99/battle_of_britain/473756.stm|title=A history of fierce football rivalry | date = 13 October 1999 | accessdate = 25 October 2007 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> whom they played annually from 1872 until 1989. The teams have met only seven times since then, most recently in June 2017.\n\nScotland have qualified for the FIFA World Cup on eight occasions and the UEFA European Championship twice, but have never progressed beyond the first group stage of a finals tournament. The last major tournament they qualified for was the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]]. The team have achieved some noteworthy results, such as beating the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]] winners England 3\u20132 at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] in 1967. [[Archie Gemmill]] scored what has been described as one of the greatest World Cup goals ever in a 3\u20132 win during the [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978 World Cup]] against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]], who reached the final of the tournament.<ref name=\"MacLeod\" /> In their qualifying group for [[UEFA Euro 2008]], Scotland defeated [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]] runners-up [[France national football team|France]] 1\u20130 in both fixtures.\n\nScotland supporters are collectively known as the [[Tartan Army]]. The Scottish Football Association operates a [[Scotland national football team roll of honour|roll of honour]] for every player who has made more than 50 [[cap (sport)|appearances]] for Scotland.<ref name=\"roll of honour\" /> [[Kenny Dalglish]] holds the record for Scotland appearances, having played 102 times between 1971 and 1986.<ref name=\"roll of honour\" /> Dalglish scored 30 goals for Scotland and shares the record for most goals scored with [[Denis Law]].\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of the Scotland national football team}}\n\n===Early history===\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n | background color = \n | image1 = 1872_engl_v_scotland_ralston.jpg\n | width1 = 150\n | alt1 = \n | image2 = 1872_engl_v_scotland-2.jpg\n | alt2 =\n | width2 = 190\n | image3 = 1872_engl_v_scotland-3.jpg\n | alt3 =\n | width3 = 94\n | image4 = 1872_engl_v_scotland-4.jpg\n | width4 = 155\n | footer_background = \n | footer_align = left\n | footer = Illustrations of the [[1872 Scotland v England football match|first international football match]], hosted by Scotland against [[England national football team|England]] in 1872}}\n\nScotland and [[England national football team|England]] are the oldest national football teams in the world.<ref name=\"oldest\">{{cite web| last=Mitchell | first=Paul | title=The first international football match | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0012/ | publisher=BBC Scotland |work= | accessdate=12 September 2013}}</ref> Teams representing the two sides first competed at [[the Oval]] in [[England v Scotland representative football matches (1870\u201372)|five matches]] between 1870 and 1872. The two countries contested [[1872 Scotland v England football match|the first official international football match]], at [[Hamilton Crescent]] in [[Partick]], Scotland, on 30 November 1872. The match ended in a goalless draw.<ref name=\"oldest\"/> All eleven players who represented Scotland that day played for [[Glasgow]] amateur club [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]].<ref name=\"oldest\" /> Over the next forty years, Scotland played matches exclusively against the other three [[Home Nations]]\u2014England, [[Wales national football team|Wales]] and [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]]. The [[British Home Championship]] began in 1883, making these games competitive. The encounters against England were particularly fierce and a [[England\u2013Scotland football rivalry|rivalry]] quickly developed.<ref name=\"them\"/>\n\nScotland lost just two of their first 43 international matches. It was not until a 2\u20130 home defeat by Ireland in 1903 that Scotland lost a match to a team other than England. This run of success meant that Scotland would have regularly topped the [[World Football Elo Ratings|Elo ratings]], which were calculated in 1998, between 1876 and 1904. Scotland won the British Home Championship outright on 24 occasions, and shared the title 17 times with at least one other team.<ref group=\"note\">The competition did not use goal difference or goal average to separate teams level on points, so the title was shared instead.</ref><ref name=\"britchamp\">{{cite web | title=British Home Championship Overview | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bhc.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate=14 May 2007}}</ref> A noteworthy victory for Scotland before the [[Second World War]] was the 5\u20131 victory over England in 1928, which led to that Scotland side being known as the \"[[Wembley Wizards]]\". Scotland played their first match outside the British Isles in 1929, beating [[Norway national football team|Norway]] 7\u20133 in [[Bergen, Norway|Bergen]].<ref name=\"euroresults\">{{cite web | title=Scotland&nbsp;\u2013 International Matches 1921\u20131930 | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scot-intres1930.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate=15 May 2007}}</ref> Scotland continued to contest regular [[exhibition game|friendly matches]] against European opposition and enjoyed wins against [[Germany national football team|Germany]] and [[France national football team|France]] before losing to the [[Austria national football team|Austrian]] \"[[Wunderteam]]\" and [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in 1931.<ref name=\"euroresults\" />\n\nScotland, like the other Home Nations, did not enter the three [[FIFA World Cup]]s held during the 1930s. This was because the four associations had been excluded from [[FIFA]] due to a disagreement regarding the status of amateur players.<ref name = \"fifa\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/federation/bodies/congress/britishassociation.html |title=The four British associations return to FIFA after the Second World War: 25th FIFA Congress in Luxembourg in 1946 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614215341/http://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/federation/bodies/congress/britishassociation.html |archivedate=14 June 2010|work=[[FIFA]] |accessdate=20 February 2010}}</ref> The four associations, including Scotland, returned to the FIFA fold after the Second World War.<ref name = \"fifa\"/> A match between a [[United Kingdom national football team|United Kingdom team]] and a [[World XI|\"Rest of the World\" team]] was played at [[Hampden Park]] in 1947 to celebrate this reconciliation.<ref name = \"fifa\"/>\n\n===1950s===\n[[File:Matt_Busby_cropped.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Matt Busby]] was due to manage Scotland at the [[1958 FIFA World Cup]], but was unable due to his injuries from the [[Munich air disaster]].]]\nThe readmission of the [[Scottish Football Association]] to FIFA meant that Scotland were now eligible to enter the [[1950 FIFA World Cup]]. FIFA advised that places would be awarded to the top two teams in the [[1950 British Home Championship]], but the SFA announced that Scotland would only attend the finals if Scotland won the competition. Scotland won their first two matches, but a 1\u20130 home defeat by [[England national football team|England]] meant that the Scots finished as runners-up. This meant that the Scots had qualified by right for the World Cup, but had not met the demand of the SFA to win the Championship. The SFA stood by this proclamation, despite pleas to the contrary by the Scotland players, supported by England captain [[Billy Wright (footballer, born 1924)|Billy Wright]] and the other England players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0001/print.shtml|title=BBC \u2013 A Sporting Nation \u2013 Scotland and the 1950 World Cup|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The SFA instead sent the Scots on a tour of North America.<ref>\"The Queens\" by Iain McCartney on Creedon Publications, 2004</ref>\n\nThe same qualification rules were in place for the [[1954 FIFA World Cup]], with the [[1954 British Home Championship]] acting as a qualifying group. Scotland again finished second, but this time the SFA allowed a team to participate in the Finals, held in Switzerland. To quote the SFA website, \"The preparation was atrocious\".<ref name=\"scottishfa.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football.cfm?curpageid=399&colour=home |publisher=Scottish Football Association |work=www.scottishfa.co.uk |title=Founding Fathers Humbled |accessdate=27 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212024531/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football.cfm?curpageid=399&colour=home |archivedate=12 December 2008}}</ref> The SFA only sent 13 players to the finals, even though FIFA allowed 22-man squads.<ref name = \"secret weapon\"/> Despite this self-imposed hardship in terms of players, the SFA dignitaries travelled in numbers, accompanied by their wives.<ref name = \"secret weapon\">{{cite news |last=Murphy |first=Alex |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/scotland/article1878706.ece |title=Docherty: spirit is Scotland\u2019s secret weapon |work=[[The Times]] |publisher=News International |date=4 June 2007 |accessdate=}}</ref> Scotland lost 1\u20130 against [[Austria national football team|Austria]] in their first game in the finals, which prompted the team [[Manager (association football)|manager]] [[Andy Beattie]] to resign hours before the game against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]].<ref>Andrew Ward, \"Scotland: The Team\" (The Breedon Book Publishing Company Limited, Derby, 1987), page 60.</ref> Uruguay were reigning champions and had never before lost a game at the World Cup finals, and they defeated Scotland 7\u20130.<ref name=\"scottishfa.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web | title=World Cup 1954 finals | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tables/54full.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate=17 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe [[1958 FIFA World Cup]] finals saw Scotland draw their first game against [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]] 1\u20131, but they then lost to [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]] and [[France national football team|France]] and went out at the first stage.<ref name = \"wsc 1958\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wsc.co.uk/the-archive/919-World-Cup/6145-law-of-averages |first=Chris |last=Freddi |title=Law of averages |work=When Saturday Comes |publisher= |date=June 1998 |accessdate=14 October 2015}}</ref> [[Matt Busby]] had been due to manage the team at the World Cup, but the severe injuries he suffered in the [[Munich air disaster]] meant that trainer [[Dawson Walker]] took charge of the team instead.<ref name = \"wsc 1958\"/>\n\n===1960s===\nUnder the management of [[Ian McColl]], Scotland enjoyed consecutive British Home Championship successes in [[1961\u201362 British Home Championship|1962]] and [[1962\u201363 British Home Championship|1963]].<ref name=\"britchamp\" /> [[Jock Stein]], [[John Prentice (footballer, born 1926)|John Prentice]] and [[Malky MacDonald]] all had brief spells as manager before [[Bobby Brown (footballer, born 1923)|Bobby Brown]] was appointed in 1967.<ref name=\"managers\">{{cite web | title=Scotland Manager Records | url= http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/man/aamanagers.html | work=www.londonhearts.com |publisher=London Hearts Supporters' Club |accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref> Brown's first match as manager was against the [[1966 FIFA World Cup|newly crowned world champions]] England at Wembley Stadium. Despite being underdogs, Scotland won 3\u20132 thanks to goals from [[Denis Law]], [[Bobby Lennox]] and [[Jim McCalliog]].<ref name=\"wizards\">{{cite web | title=Wembley Wizards 1967 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0022/page03.shtml | publisher=BBC Scotland | accessdate=15 May 2007}}</ref> Having defeated the world champions on their own turf, the Scotland fans hailed their team as the \"[[Unofficial Football World Championships|unofficial world champions]]\".<ref>{{cite book | author=Paul Brown | title=The Unofficial Football World Championships | publisher=Tonto Sport |year=2006 | isbn=0-9552183-1-4}}</ref> Despite this famous win, the Scots failed to qualify for any major competitions during the 1960s.<ref name = \"wsc 1958\"/>\n\n===1970s===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-N0614-0028, Fu\u00dfball-WM, Zaire - Schottland 0-2.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Billy Bremner]] (right) playing for Scotland against [[Zaire national football team|Zaire]] at the [[Westfalenstadion]] in the [[1974 FIFA World Cup]]]]\nAfter [[Tommy Docherty]]'s brief spell as manager, [[Willie Ormond]] was hired in 1973.<ref name=\"managers\" /> Ormond lost his first match in charge 5\u20130 to England, but recovered to steer Scotland to their first World Cup finals in 16 years in 1974. At the [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974 World Cup]] finals in [[West Germany]], Scotland achieved their most impressive performance at a World Cup tournament.<ref name = \"1974 best\">{{cite news |last=Hepburn |first=Ray |work=[[Sunday Mirror]] |date=21 March 2010 |accessdate=28 July 2010 |url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/opinion/columnists/ray-hepburn/Why-the-Scotland-1974-World-Cup-side-gets-my-vote-as-best-ever-The-Ray-Hepburn-Column-article362351.html |title=Why the Scotland 1974 World Cup side gets my vote as best ever}}</ref> The team was unbeaten but failed to progress beyond the group stages on [[goal difference]].<ref name = \"1974 best\"/> After beating [[DR Congo national football team|Za\u00efre]], they drew with both [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] and [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]], and went out because they had beaten Za\u00efre by the smallest margin.<ref name=\"brazil74\" />\n\nScotland appointed [[Ally MacLeod]] as manager in 1977, with qualification for the [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978 World Cup]] in [[Argentina]] far from assured.<ref name=\"managers\" /> The team made a strong start under MacLeod by winning the [[1977 British Home Championship]], largely thanks to a 2\u20131 victory over England at Wembley.<ref name=\"britchamp\" /> The [[Tartan Army|Scotland fans]] invaded the pitch after the match, ripping up the turf and breaking a crossbar.<ref>{{cite news | title=Scots stash souvenirs under Wembley | url= http://news.scotsman.com/weirdoddandquirkystories/Scots-stash-souvenirs-under-Wembley.3359192.jp |work=The Scotsman | date=1 April 2007 | accessdate=21 September 2008 | location=Edinburgh | first=Nicholas | last=Christian}}</ref> Scotland's good form continued as they secured qualification for the World Cup with victories over [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] and [[Wales national football team|Wales]].<ref name=\"rsssf.com\">{{cite web | title=Scotland&nbsp;\u2013 International Matches 1976\u20131980 | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scot-intres1980.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate=15 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nDuring the build-up to the [[1978 FIFA World Cup]], MacLeod fuelled the hopes of the nation by stating that Scotland would come home with a medal.<ref name=\"MacLeod\">{{cite web | title=1978 World Cup | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0002/print.shtml | publisher=BBC Scotland | accessdate=15 May 2007}}</ref> As the squad left for the finals in Argentina, they were given an enthusiastic send-off as they were paraded around a packed [[Hampden Park]].<ref>{{cite web | last=Aitken |first=Mike | title=Ally MacLeod, a tragic hero | url= http://sport.scotsman.com/allymacleod/Ally-MacLeod-a-tragic-hero.2500029.jp |work=The Scotsman | date=2 February 2004 | accessdate=8 January 2008}}</ref> Thousands more fans lined the route to [[Glasgow Prestwick International Airport|Prestwick Airport]] as the team set off for [[South America]].<ref name=\"MacLeod\" /> Scotland's first game was against [[Peru national football team|Peru]] in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]]. Two spectacular goals by [[Te\u00f3filo Cubillas]] meant that the result was a 3\u20131 loss. The second game was a very disappointing 1\u20131 draw against newcomers [[Iran national football team|Iran]].<ref name=\"MacLeod\" /> The disconsolate mood of the nation was reflected by footage of Ally MacLeod in the [[Technical area|dugout]] with his head in his hands.<ref>{{cite news | title=Ally McLeod&nbsp;\u2013 a national treasure | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/3468549.stm | first=Chick |last=Young | publisher =BBC Sport | date=7 February 2004 | accessdate=15 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nAfter taking a single point from their opening two games, Scotland had to defeat the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] by three clear goals to progress.<ref name=\"cup78\" /> Despite the Dutch taking the lead, Scotland fought back to win 3\u20132 with a goal from [[Kenny Dalglish]] and two from [[Archie Gemmill]], the second of which is considered one of the greatest World Cup goals ever;<ref name=\"MacLeod\" /> Gemmill beat three Dutch defenders before lifting the ball over goalkeeper [[Jan Jongbloed]] into the net.<ref name=\"MacLeod\" /><ref name=\"gemmill\">{{cite web | title=The lion roars&nbsp;\u2013 too late | url=http://sport.scotsman.com/tengreatfootballmatches/The-lion-roars--too.2379220.jp |work=The Scotsman | date=19 November 2002 | accessdate=8 January 2008}}</ref> The victory was not sufficient to secure a place in the second round, and Scotland were eliminated on goal difference for the second successive World Cup.<ref name=\"cup78\" />\n\n===1980s===\n[[File:Alex_Ferguson.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Alex Ferguson]] (pictured) briefly served as Scotland's manager after the sudden death of [[Jock Stein]] in 1985.]]\nMacLeod resigned as manager shortly after the 1978 World Cup, and [[Jock Stein]], who had won nine consecutive [[list of Scottish football champions|Scottish league titles]] and the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] as manager of [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], was appointed as his successor.<ref name=\"managers\" /> After failing to qualify for the [[UEFA Euro 1980|1980 European Championship]],<ref name=\"rsssf.com\"/> Scotland qualified for the [[1982 FIFA World Cup]] from a tough group including [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]], [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], [[Israel national football team|Israel]] and [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]], losing just one match in the process.<ref>{{cite web |title=Scotland&nbsp;\u2013 International Matches 1981\u20131985 |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scot-intres1985.html |publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation |accessdate=15 May 2007}}</ref> They beat [[New Zealand national football team|New Zealand]] 5\u20132 in their first game at the World Cup, but lost 4\u20131 to a [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] team containing [[S\u00f3crates]], [[Zico]], [[\u00c9der Aleixo de Assis|Eder]] and [[Paulo Roberto Falc\u00e3o|Falc\u00e3o]].<ref name=\"cup82\" /> Scotland were again eliminated on goal difference, after a 2\u20132 draw with the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]].<ref name=\"cup82\" />\n\nScotland qualified for the [[1986 FIFA World Cup]], their fourth in succession, in traumatic circumstances. The squad went into their [[1985 Wales vs Scotland football match|last qualification match against Wales]] needing a point to progress to a qualifying playoff against [[Australia national association football team|Australia]]. With only nine minutes remaining and Wales leading 1\u20130, Scotland were awarded a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]], which was calmly scored by [[Davie Cooper]].<ref name=\"stein\">{{cite web | last=Brown |first=Craig | title=Stein, a national treasure | url= http://sport.scotsman.com/jockstein/Stein-a-national-treasure.2660236.jp |work=The Scotsman | date=11 September 2005 | accessdate=8 January 2008}}</ref> The 1\u20131 draw meant that Scotland progressed, but as the players and fans celebrated, Stein suffered a heart attack and died shortly afterwards.<ref name=\"stein\" /> His assistant [[Alex Ferguson]] took over.<ref name=\"managers\" /> Scotland qualified by winning 2\u20130 against Australia in a two-leg playoff, but were eliminated from the tournament with just one point from their three matches, a goalless draw with [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] following defeats by [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] and [[West Germany national football team|West Germany]].<ref>{{cite web | title=World Cup 1986 | url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/86full.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate=14 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1986, [[Andy Roxburgh]] was the surprise appointment as the new manager of Scotland.<ref name = \"rox\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DQ5BAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4aYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6100%2C3875913 |title=Scotland on a winner |newspaper=Evening Times |first=Chick |last=Young |date=17 July 1986 |page=20 |accessdate=20 October 2012}}</ref> Scotland did not succeed in qualifying for [[UEFA Euro 1988|Euro 1988]], but their 1\u20130 away win over [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] in the final fixture in November 1987 helped [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Ireland]] to a surprise first-place finish and qualification for the finals in [[West Germany]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Davidson|first=Alan|title=Too late but new boys look good for future|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gNBAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=kKYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6004%2C2954712|accessdate=12 April 2015|work=Evening Times|date=12 November 1987|page=26}}</ref>\n\n===1990s===\nScotland qualified for their fifth consecutive [[1990 FIFA World Cup|World Cup in 1990]] by finishing second in their qualifying group, ahead of [[France national football team|France]].<ref>{{cite web | title=World Cup 1990 Qualifying | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/90q.html | accessdate=31 August 2008}}</ref> Scotland were drawn in a group with [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]], Sweden, and Brazil, but the Scots lost 1\u20130 to Costa Rica.<ref name = \"Italy 90\">{{cite web | title=World Cup 1990 (Italy, 8 June&nbsp;\u2013 8 July) | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/90f.html | accessdate=31 August 2008}}</ref> While they recovered to beat Sweden 2\u20131 in their second game, they lost to Brazil in their third match 1\u20130 and were again eliminated after the first round.<ref name = \"Italy 90\"/>\n\nBy a narrow margin, Scotland qualified for the [[UEFA European Championship]] for the first time in [[UEFA Euro 1992|1992]].<ref name=\"sweden\">{{cite web|title=1992&nbsp;\u2013 Small but perfectly formed |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/euro/history/season=1992/intro.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070421035254/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/euro/history/season%3D1992/intro.html |archivedate=21 April 2007 |publisher=UEFA |date=5 October 2003 |accessdate=15 May 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A 1\u20130 defeat by [[Romania national football team|Romania]] away from home left qualification dependent upon other results, but a 1\u20131 draw between [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] and Romania in the final group match saw Scotland squeeze through.<ref name=\"euro92\">{{cite web | title=European Championship 1992 | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tables/92e.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate=15 May 2007}}</ref> Despite playing well in matches against the Netherlands and Germany and a fine win against the [[CIS national football team|CIS]], the team was knocked out at the group stage.<ref name=\"euro92\" /> Scotland failed to qualify for the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]]. The team finished fourth in their [[1994 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualifying group]] behind [[Italy national football team|Italy]], [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] and Portugal. When it became clear that Scotland could not qualify, [[Andy Roxburgh]] resigned from his position as team manager.<ref name = \"Brown highs and lows\">{{cite web | title=Craig Brown's highs and lows |publisher=BBC Sport |work= | date=7 October 2001 | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/1528293.stm | accessdate=31 August 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Scotland-holland euro 96.jpg|thumb|right|Scotland against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] at [[Villa Park]] during [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 1996]]]]\nNew manager [[Craig Brown (footballer, born 1940)|Craig Brown]] successfully guided Scotland to the [[UEFA Euro 1996|1996 European Championship]] tournament.<ref name = \"Brown highs and lows\"/> The first game against the Netherlands ended 0\u20130, raising morale ahead of a much anticipated game against England at Wembley.<ref name = \"Brown highs and lows\"/> [[Gary McAllister]] missed a penalty kick, and a goal by [[Paul Gascoigne]] led to a 2\u20130 defeat. Scotland recovered to beat [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] 1\u20130 with a goal by [[Ally McCoist]]. England taking a 4\u20130 lead in the other match briefly put both teams in a position to qualify, but a late goal for the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] meant that Scotland were knocked out on goals scored.<ref name = \"Brown highs and lows\"/><ref name=england96>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-intres95.html|title=England: International results 1995\u20131999 details|publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]|accessdate=18 July 2010 |date=14 March 2004|first=Barrie |last=Courtney}}</ref>\n\nBrown again guided Scotland to qualification for a major tournament in 1998, and Scotland were drawn against Brazil in the opening game of the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Scotland Open the World Cup 1998 | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/sportscotland/asportingnation/article/0042/ | publisher=BBC Scotland |work= | accessdate=16 May 2007}}</ref> [[John Collins (footballer, born 1968)|John Collins]] equalised from the penalty spot to level the score at 1\u20131, but a [[Tom Boyd (Scottish footballer)|Tom Boyd]] [[own goal]] led to a 2\u20131 defeat. Scotland drew their next game 1\u20131 with Norway in [[Bordeaux]],<ref name=\"burley\" /> but the final match against [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] ended in an embarrassing 3\u20130 defeat.<ref name = \"Brown highs and lows\"/>\n\nDuring the qualification for the [[UEFA Euro 2000|2000 European Championship]], Scotland faced England in a [[two-legged tie|two-legged]] playoff nicknamed the \"Battle of Britain\" by the media.<ref name=\"wembley1-0\">{{cite web| title=Battle of Britain | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/special_report/1999/11/99/battle_of_britain/525203.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |work= | date=17 November 1999 | accessdate=11 April 2007}}</ref> Scotland won the second match 1\u20130 with a goal by [[Don Hutchison]], but lost the tie 2\u20131 on aggregate.<ref name=\"wembley1-0\" />\n\n===2000s===\n[[File:Berti Vogts cropped.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Berti Vogts]], the only foreigner to coach Scotland to date]]\nScotland failed to qualify for the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]], finishing third in their qualifying group behind [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] and [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]].<ref name = \"Brown highs and lows\"/> This second successive failure to qualify prompted Craig Brown to resign from his position after the final qualifying match.<ref name = \"Brown highs and lows\"/> The [[Scottish Football Association|SFA]] appointed former Germany manager [[Berti Vogts]] as Brown's successor.<ref>{{cite web| title=Vogts unveiled by Scotland | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/1822296.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |work= | date=15 February 2002 | accessdate=12 April 2007}}</ref> Scotland reached the qualification play-offs for [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]], where they beat the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] 1\u20130 at Hampden Park, but suffered a 6\u20130 defeat in the return leg. Poor results in friendly matches and a bad start to the 2006 World Cup qualification caused the team to drop to a record low of 77th in the [[FIFA World Rankings]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Scotland hit new low in rankings | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/3998817.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |work= |date=10 November 2004 | accessdate=12 April 2007}}</ref> Vogts announced his resignation in 2004,<ref>{{cite web | title=Vogts resigns from Scotland job | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/3734094.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |work= | date=1 November 2004 | accessdate=12 April 2007}}</ref> blaming the hostile media for his departure.<ref>{{cite web | title=Berti Vogts personal statement | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/3972921.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |work= | date=1 November 2004 | accessdate=12 April 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[Walter Smith]], a former [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] manager, was brought in to replace Vogts. Improved results meant that Scotland rose up the FIFA rankings and won the [[Kirin Cup]], a friendly competition in Japan.<ref>{{cite web| title=Japan 0\u20130 Scotland | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4765811.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |work= | date=13 May 2006 | accessdate=11 April 2007}}</ref> Scotland failed to qualify for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]], finishing third in their group behind [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and [[Norway national football team|Norway]]. Smith left the national side in January 2007 to return to [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], with Scotland leading their [[2008 UEFA European Championship|Euro 2008]] qualification group.<ref>{{cite web| title=Smith appointed boss of Rangers | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/6233237.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |work= | date=10 January 2007 | accessdate=12 April 2007}}</ref> [[Alex McLeish]] was named as Smith's successor and Scotland's twentieth manager.<ref>{{cite web| title=McLeish unveiled as Scotland boss | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/6289073.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |work= | date=29 January 2007 | accessdate=12 April 2007}}</ref> McLeish guided Scotland to wins against [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]], the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]], [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]], France and [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]], but defeats by Georgia and Italy ended their chances of qualification for Euro 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7115771.stm|title=Rise and fall of McLeish's Scotland|date=27 November 2007|accessdate=2 February 2008|publisher=BBC Sport |work=}}</ref> These improved results, particularly the wins against France, lifted Scotland into the top 20 of the FIFA world rankings.<ref name = \"peak ranking\"/>\n\nAfter the narrow failure to qualify for Euro 2008, McLeish left to join [[Premier League]] club [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].<ref>{{cite web| title = McLeish leaves Scotland for Blues |publisher=BBC Sport |work= | date = 27 November 2007 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7114028.stm | accessdate = 27 September 2008 }}</ref> [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] manager [[George Burley]] was hired as the new manager, but he came in for criticism from the media after the team lost their first qualifier against [[Macedonia national football team|Macedonia]].<ref>{{cite news| last = Hunter | first = Andy | title = Fletcher backs Burley as McCulloch deepens woe |work=The Guardian | date = 9 September 2008 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/sep/09/worldcup2010qualifiers.scotlandfootballteam | accessdate = 27 September 2008 | location=London}}</ref> After Scotland lost their fourth match 3\u20130 to the Netherlands,<ref>{{cite web| last =Moffat | first =Colin | title = Netherlands 3\u20130 Scotland |publisher=BBC Sport |work= | date = 28 March 2009 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7963110.stm | accessdate = 31 March 2009 }}</ref> captain [[Barry Ferguson]] and goalkeeper [[Allan McGregor]] were excluded from the starting lineup for the following match against [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] due to a \"breach of discipline\".<ref>{{cite web| title = Scots duo breach to be reviewed |publisher=BBC Sport |work= |date = 1 April 2009 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7977741.stm | accessdate = 2 April 2009 }}</ref> Despite winning 2\u20131 against Iceland,<ref>{{cite web |last=Moffat |first=Colin |title=Scotland 2\u20131 Iceland |publisher=BBC Sport |work= |date=1 April 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7971845.stm |accessdate=2 April 2009}}</ref> Scotland suffered a terrible 4\u20130 defeat by Norway in the following qualifier, which left Scotland effectively needing to win their last two games to have a realistic chance of making the qualifying play-offs.<ref>{{cite web | last =Moffat | first =Colin | title = Scotland can bounce back&nbsp;\u2013 Burley |publisher=BBC Sport |work= | date = 13 August 2009 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/8194452.stm | accessdate = 6 September 2009 }}</ref> Scotland defeated Macedonia 2\u20130 in the first of those two games,<ref>{{cite web | last =Moffat | first =Colin | title = Scotland 2\u20130 Macedonia |publisher=BBC Sport |work= | date = 5 September 2009 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/8230555.stm | accessdate = 6 September 2009 }}</ref> but were eliminated by a 1\u20130 loss to the Netherlands in the second game.<ref>{{cite web | last =Lindsay | first =Clive | title = Scotland 0\u20131 Netherlands |publisher=BBC Sport |work= | date = 9 September 2009 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/8240464.stm | accessdate = 9 September 2009 }}</ref> Burley was allowed to continue in his post after a review by the SFA board,<ref>{{cite web | title = Burley remains as Scotland boss |publisher=BBC Sport |work= | date = 15 September 2009 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/8256276.stm | accessdate = 16 September 2009 }}</ref> but a subsequent 3\u20130 friendly defeat by Wales led to the SFA sacking him.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/8361602.stm |title=Burley sacked as Scotland manager |publisher=BBC Sport |work= |accessdate=16 November 2009 | date=16 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n===2010s===\n[[File:Strachan Gordon.jpg|thumb|[[Gordon Strachan]] was appointed Scotland manager in January 2013.]]\nThe SFA appointed [[Craig Levein]] as head coach of the national team in December 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/8424274.stm |title=Levein appointed Scotland manager |publisher=BBC Sport |work= |date=23 December 2009 |accessdate=16 October 2010 }}</ref> In [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying]], Scotland were grouped with [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]], [[Liechtenstein national football team|Liechtenstein]], the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] and world champions [[Spain national football team|Spain]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/8970226.stm |title=Scotland 2\u20131 Liechtenstein |publisher=BBC Sport |work= |date=7 September 2010 |accessdate=7 September 2010 |last=Lindsay |first=Clive}}</ref><ref name = \"three wins\"/> They took just four points from the first four games, leaving the team needing three wins from their remaining four games to have a realistic chance of progression.<ref name = \"three wins\">{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/more-scottish-football/miller-insists-three-wins-will-seal-play-off-place-1.1061204 |title=Miller insists three wins will seal play-off place |work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] |date=13 October 2010 |accessdate=13 October 2010 |last=Macpherson |first=Graeme}}</ref> They only managed two wins and a draw and were eliminated after a 3\u20131 defeat by Spain in their last match.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/15232020.stm|first=Annie|last=McGuire |title=Spain 3\u20131 Scotland|publisher=BBC Sport |work= |date=11 October 2011 |accessdate=11 October 2011}}</ref> Levein left his position as head coach following a poor start to [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification]], having taken just two points from four games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20205303 |title=Craig Levein exits as Scotland coach following talks |first=Chris |last=McLaughlin |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=5 November 2012 |accessdate=5 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Gordon Strachan]] was appointed Scotland manager in January 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21023913 |title=Gordon Strachan confirmed as Scotland coach |first=Chris |last=McLaughlin |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 January 2013 |accessdate=15 January 2013}}</ref> but defeats in his first two competitive matches meant that Scotland were the first UEFA team to be eliminated from the 2014 World Cup.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/international/219124-scotland-officially-first-uefa-nation-eliminated-from-world-cup-qualifying/ |title=Scotland officially first UEFA nation eliminated from World Cup qualifying |first=Grant |last=Russell |work= |publisher=STV Sport |date=26 March 2013 |accessdate=26 March 2013}}</ref> Scotland finished their qualification section by winning three of their last four matches, including two victories against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22787925 |title=Croatia 0\u20131 Scotland |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |first=Alasdair |last=Lamont |date=7 June 2013 |accessdate=8 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24439813 |title=Scotland 2\u20130 Croatia |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |first=Alasdair |last=Lamont |date=15 October 2013 |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref> In [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying]], Scotland appeared to have a better chance of qualification as the finals tournament was expanded from 16 teams to 24.<ref name = \"bumpy\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34532300 |title=A bumpy ride: Gordon Strachan and Scotland |first=Andy |last=Burke |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=16 October 2015 |accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref> After losing their opening match in [[Germany national football team|Germany]], Scotland recorded home wins against [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]], the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] and [[Gibraltar national football team|Gibraltar]].<ref name = \"bumpy\"/> [[Steven Fletcher (footballer)|Steven Fletcher]] scored the first [[hat-trick]] for Scotland since 1969 in the game with Gibraltar.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32006329 |title=Scotland 6&ndash;1 Gibraltar |first=Alasdair |last=Lamont |website= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 March 2015 |accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref> Later in the group, Scotland produced an \"insipid\" performance as they lost 1\u20130 in Georgia.<ref name = \"bumpy\"/> A home defeat by Germany and a late equalising goal by [[Poland national football team|Poland]] eliminated Scotland from contention.<ref name = \"bumpy\"/> After a win against Gibraltar in the last qualifier, Strachan agreed a new contract with the SFA.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34540057 |title=Gordon Strachan: Scotland boss signs new two-year contract |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=16 October 2015 |accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualification]] for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], Scotland were drawn in the same group as England, facing their rivals in a competitive fixture for the first time since 1999.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|title=England to play World Cup qualifier against Scotland on a Friday night|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/jul/26/england-scotland-world-cup-2018-qualifier-friday-night|accessdate=20 October 2015|work=The Guardian|agency=Press Association|date=26 July 2015}}</ref> On 11 November 2016, England beat Scotland 3\u20130 at Wembley.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37868651|title=World Cup Qualifying \u2013 European \u2013 Group F|work= |publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 November 2016|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref> The return match saw [[Leigh Griffiths]] score two late free-kicks to give Scotland a 2\u20131 lead, but [[Harry Kane]] scored in added time to force a 2\u20132 draw.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40141512 |title=Scotland 2\u20132 England |first=Phil |last=McNulty |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=10 June 2017 |accessdate=14 June 2017}}</ref> A draw in [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]] in the final game of the group ended Scottish hopes of a play-off position, and Strachan subsequently left his position by mutual consent.<ref>{{cite news|title=Scotland: Gordon Strachan leaves his position as national manager|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41598733|accessdate=12 October 2017|publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 October 2017}}</ref> In February 2018, Alex McLeish was appointed manager for the second time.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Murray|first1=Ewan|title=Alex McLeish says it was his \u2018destiny\u2019 to return as Scotland manager|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/feb/16/football-scotland-manager-alex-mcleish|accessdate=17 March 2018|work=The Guardian|date=16 February 2018}}</ref> The team won their group in the [[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League]], but McLeish left in April 2019 after a poor start to [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying]], including a 3\u20130 loss to 117th-ranked [[Kazakhstan national football team|Kazakhstan]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Scotland: Alex McLeish exits after poor start to Euro 2020 qualifying |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47767790 |accessdate=18 April 2019 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=18 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Competitive record==\n{{See also|Scotland national football team results}}\n\n===FIFA World Cup===\n{{Main|Scotland at the FIFA World Cup}}\nScotland did not compete in the first three World Cup competitions, held in [[1930 FIFA World Cup|1930]], [[1934 FIFA World Cup|1934]] and [[1938 FIFA World Cup|1938]]. [[FIFA]] ruled that all its member associations must provide \"broken-time\" payments to cover the expenses of players who participated in [[football at the 1928 Summer Olympics]]. In response to what they considered to be unacceptable interference, the football associations of Scotland, England, Ireland and Wales held a meeting at which they agreed to resign from FIFA.<ref>{{cite web|title=British Society of Sports History |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/development/technical/index/0,1250,7758,00.html?articleid=7758 |publisher=FIFA |date=19 August 1999 |accessdate=31 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050904111234/http://fifa.com/en/development/technical/index/0%2C1250%2C7758%2C00.html?articleid=7758 |archivedate=4 September 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The [[Scottish Football Association]] did not rejoin FIFA as a permanent member until 1946.<ref name = \"fifa member\">{{cite web | title=Between the Wars | url= http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football.cfm?curpageid=397 | publisher=Scottish Football Association | accessdate=30 May 2007}}</ref> The SFA declined to participate in [[1950 FIFA World Cup|1950]] although they had qualified, as Scotland were not the [[British Home Championship|British champions]].<ref name = \"withdrew\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/50q.html |title=World Cup 1950 Qualifying |accessdate=20 May 2010 |publisher=[[RSSSF]]}}</ref>\n\nScotland have since qualified for eight finals tournaments,<ref name=\"burley\">{{cite news | title= Burley move pays off for Scotland | url= http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/world/events/1998/worldcup/news/1998/06/16/scotland_first/ | publisher=CNN | date=28 September 1998 | accessdate=12 April 2007}}</ref> including five consecutive tournaments from [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974]] to [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990]]. Scotland have never advanced beyond the first round of the finals competition&nbsp;\u2013 no country has qualified for as many World Cup finals without progressing past the first round. They have missed out on progressing to the second round three times on goal difference: in [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974]], when [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] edged them out;<ref name=\"brazil74\">{{cite web | title=World Cup 1974 finals | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tables/74full.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate=14 September 2008}}</ref> in [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]], when the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] progressed;<ref name=\"cup78\">{{cite web | title=World Cup 1978 finals| url= http://www.rsssf.com/tables/78full.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate=14 September 2008}}</ref> and in [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]], when the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]] went through.<ref name=\"cup82\">{{cite web | title=World Cup 1982 finals | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tables/82full.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate=14 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;font-size:90%;\"   \n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n!colspan=\"8\"|[[FIFA World Cup|Final Tournament]]\n!colspan=\"7\"|[[FIFA World Cup qualification|Qualification]]\n|-\n!Host nation(s)\n!Round\n!{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|F|Goals scored}}\n!{{Tooltip|A|Goals conceded}}\n!Round\n!{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|F|Goals scored}}\n!{{Tooltip|A|Goals conceded}}\n|- \n|[[1930 FIFA World Cup|1930]]||Uruguay||colspan=14 rowspan=3|''Did not enter''<ref name = \"fifa member\"/>\n|-\n|[[1934 FIFA World Cup|1934]]||Italy\n|-\n|[[1938 FIFA World Cup|1938]]||France\n|-\n|[[1950 FIFA World Cup|1950]]||Brazil||colspan=7 rowspan=1|''Qualified but withdrew''<ref name = \"withdrew\"/>||'''[[1949\u201350 British Home Championship|Group \u2013 2nd]]'''||3||2||0||1||10||3\n|-   \n|[[1954 FIFA World Cup|1954]]||Switzerland||Round 1||2||0||0||2||0||8||'''[[1953\u201354 British Home Championship|Group \u2013 2nd]]'''||3||1||1||1||8||8\n|-   \n|[[1958 FIFA World Cup|1958]]||Sweden||Round 1||3||0||1||2||4||6||'''[[1958 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA \u2013 Group 9)|Group \u2013 1st]]'''||4||3||0||1||10||9\n|-\n|[[1962 FIFA World Cup|1962]]||Chile||colspan=7 rowspan=3|''Did not qualify''||[[1962 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA - Group 8)|Group \u2013 2nd]]||5||3||0||2||12||11\n|-\n|[[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966]]||England||[[1966 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA \u2013 Group 8)|Group \u2013 2nd]]||6||3||1||2||8||8\n|-\n|[[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970]]||Mexico||[[1970 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)#Group 7|Group \u2013 2nd]]||6||3||1||2||18||7\n|-\n|[[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974]]||West Germany||Round 1||3||1||2||0||3||1||'''[[1974 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)#Group 8|Group \u2013 1st]]'''||4||3||0||1||8||3\n|-\n|[[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]]||Argentina||Round 1||3||1||1||1||5||6||'''[[1978 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)#Group 7|Group \u2013 1st]]'''||4||3||0||1||6||3\n|-\n|[[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]]||Spain||Round 1||3||1||1||1||8||8||'''[[1982 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 6|Group \u2013 1st]]'''||8||4||3||1||9||4\n|-\n|[[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]]||Mexico||Round 1||3||0||1||2||1||3||'''[[1986 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA\u2013OFC play-off)|Play-off]]'''||8||4||2||2||10||4\n|-\n|[[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990]]||Italy||Round 1||3||1||0||2||2||3||'''[[1990 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 5|Group \u2013 2nd]]'''||8||4||2||2||12||12\n|-\n|[[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]]||United States||colspan=7 rowspan=1|''Did not qualify''||[[1994 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA \u2013 Group 1)|Group \u2013 4th]]||10||4||3||3||14||13\n|-\n|[[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]]||France||Round 1||3||0||1||2||2||6||'''[[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 4|Group \u2013 2nd]]'''||10||7||2||1||15||3\n|-\n|[[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002]]||South Korea; Japan||colspan=7 rowspan=5|''Did not qualify''||[[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 6|Group \u2013 3rd]]||8||4||3||1||12||6\n|-\n|[[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006]]||Germany||[[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 5|Group \u2013 3rd]]||10||3||4||3||9||7\n|-\n|[[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]]||South Africa||[[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 9|Group \u2013 3rd]]||8||3||1||4||6||11\n|-\n|[[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]]||Brazil||[[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group A|Group \u2013 4th]]||10||3||2||5||8||12\n|-\n|[[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]]||Russia||[[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group F|Group \u2013 3rd]]||10||5||3||2||17||12\n|-\n!Totals!!8/21!!!!23!!4!!7!!12!!25!!41|| !!125!!62!!28!!35!!192!!136\n|}\n\n===UEFA European Championship===\n{{main|Scotland at the UEFA European Championship}}\nScotland have qualified for two [[UEFA European Championship|European Championships]], but have failed to advance beyond the first round on both occasions. Their most recent participation was at the [[UEFA Euro 1996|1996 European Championship]], where the Netherlands progressed instead of Scotland on [[goal difference|goals scored]].<ref name=\"Euro\">{{cite web|title=Prognosis positive for Scotland |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/euro/teams/team=117/kindstatic=16/index.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080205070310/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/euro/teams/team%3D117/kindstatic%3D16/index.html |archivedate=5 February 2008 |publisher=UEFA |date=8 January 2006 |accessdate=17 September 2008 |url-status=dead }} (archive.org mirror)</ref> Scotland is due to host three group games and a last 16 match in [[UEFA Euro 2020]], which is being held at venues across Europe.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://stv.tv/sport/football/1403906-hampden-loses-out-on-hosting-opening-match-of-euro-2020/ |title=Hampden loses out on hosting opening match of Euro 2020 |first=Andy |last=Coyle |work= |publisher=STV Sport |date=7 December 2017 |accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;font-size:90%;\"   \n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n!colspan=\"8\"|[[UEFA European Championship|Final Tournament]]\n!colspan=\"7\"|[[UEFA European Championship qualifying|Qualification]]\n|-\n!Host nation(s)\n!Round\n!{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|F|Goals scored}}\n!{{Tooltip|A|Goals conceded}}\n!Round\n!{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|F|Goals scored}}\n!{{Tooltip|A|Goals conceded}}\n|- \n|[[1960 European Nations' Cup|1960]]||France||colspan=14 rowspan=2|''Did not enter''\n|-\n|[[1964 European Nations' Cup|1964]]||Spain\n|-\n|[[UEFA Euro 1968|1968]]||Italy||colspan=7 rowspan=6|''Did not qualify'' ||[[UEFA Euro 1968 qualifying Group 8|Group \u2013 2nd]] ||6||3||2||1||10||8\n|-\n|[[UEFA Euro 1972|1972]]||Belgium||[[UEFA Euro 1972 qualifying Group 5|Group \u2013 3rd]]||6||3||0||3||4||7\n|-\n|[[UEFA Euro 1976|1976]]||Yugoslavia||[[UEFA Euro 1976 qualifying Group 4|Group \u2013 3rd]]||6||2||3||1||8||6\n|-\n|[[UEFA Euro 1980|1980]]||Italy||[[UEFA Euro 1980 qualifying Group 2|Group \u2013 4th]]||8||3||1||4||15||13\n|-\n|[[UEFA Euro 1984|1984]]||France||[[UEFA Euro 1984 qualifying Group 1|Group \u2013 4th]]||6||1||2||3||8||10\n|-\n|[[UEFA Euro 1988|1988]]||West Germany||[[UEFA Euro 1988 qualifying Group 7|Group \u2013 4th]]||8||3||3||2||7||5\n|-\n|[[UEFA Euro 1992|1992]]||Sweden||Round 1||3||1||0||2||3||3||'''[[UEFA Euro 1992 qualifying Group 2|Group \u2013 1st]]'''||8||4||3||1||14||7\n|-\n|[[UEFA Euro 1996|1996]]||England||Round 1||3||1||1||1||1||2||'''[[UEFA Euro 1996 qualifying Group 8|Group \u2013 2nd]]'''||10||7||2||1||19||3\n|-\n|[[UEFA Euro 2000|2000]]||Belgium; Netherlands||colspan=7 rowspan=5|''Did not qualify''||[[UEFA Euro 2000 qualifying play-offs|Play-offs]]||12||6||3||3||16||12\n|-\n|[[UEFA Euro 2004|2004]]||Portugal||[[UEFA Euro 2004 qualifying play-offs|Play-offs]]||10||5||2||3||13||14\n|-\n|[[UEFA Euro 2008|2008]]||Switzerland; Austria||[[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying Group B|Group \u2013 3rd]]||12||8||0||4||21||12\n|-\n|[[UEFA Euro 2012|2012]]||Poland; Ukraine||[[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying Group I|Group \u2013 3rd]]||8||3||2||3||9||10\n|-\n|[[UEFA Euro 2016|2016]]||France||[[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying Group D|Group \u2013 4th]]||10||4||3||3||22||12\n|-\n|style=\"border: 3px solid red\"|[[UEFA Euro 2020|2020]]||style=\"border: 3px solid red\"|Several||colspan=7|''TBD''||''[[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying Group I|Play-offs]]''||10||5||0||5||16||19\n|-\n!Totals!!2/15!!!!6!!2!!1!!3!!4!!5|| !!120!!57!!26!!37!!182!!138\n|-\n|}\n\n===UEFA Nations League===\nWhen the [[UEFA Nations League]] was inaugurated in [[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League|2018\u201319]], Scotland were allocated to [[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League C|League C]]. With a 3\u20132 win against [[Israel national football team|Israel]] in their final match, Scotland won promotion to [[2020\u201321 UEFA Nations League B|League B]] of the [[2020\u201321 UEFA Nations League|2020\u201321]] competition.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46189774 |title=Scotland 3\u20132 Israel |first=Alasdair |last=Lamont |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 November 2018 |accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!colspan=12|[[UEFA Nations League]] record\n|-\n!Season\n!Division\n!Group\n!Round\n!width=28|{{Tooltip|Pos|Position}}\n!width=28|{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!width=28|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=28|{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!width=28|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!width=28|{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!width=28|{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!width=28|{{Tooltip|P/R|Promotion/relegation at end of season}}\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League|2018\u201319]]\n|[[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League C|C]]\n|[[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League C#Group 1|1]]\n|rowspan=2|Group stage\n|1st||4||3||0||1||10||4||{{rise}}\n|-\n|[[2020\u201321 UEFA Nations League|2020\u201321]]\n|[[2020\u201321 UEFA Nations League#League B|B]]\n|\u2014\n|rowspan=1 colspan=7|''To be determined''\n|{{n/a}}\n|-\n!rowspan=1 colspan=5|'''Totals'''\n!4\n!3\n!0\n!1\n!10\n!4\n!\u2014\n|}\n\n===Other honours===\n*'''[[British Home Championship]]'''\n**'''''Winners (24)''''': [[1884 British Home Championship|1884]], [[1885 British Home Championship|1885]], [[1887 British Home Championship|1887]], [[1889 British Home Championship|1889]], [[1894 British Home Championship|1894]], [[1896 British Home Championship|1896]], [[1897 British Home Championship|1897]], [[1900 British Home Championship|1900]], [[1902 British Home Championship|1902]], [[1910 British Home Championship|1910]], [[1921 British Home Championship|1921]], [[1922 British Home Championship|1922]], [[1923 British Home Championship|1923]], [[1929 British Home Championship|1929]], [[1935 British Home Championship|1935]], [[1936 British Home Championship|1936]], [[1946 unofficial British Home Championship|1946]], [[1949 British Home Championship|1949]], [[1951 British Home Championship|1951]], [[1962 British Home Championship|1962]], [[1963 British Home Championship|1963]], [[1967 British Home Championship|1967]], [[1976 British Home Championship|1976]], [[1977 British Home Championship|1977]]\n**'''''Shared (17)''''': [[1886 British Home Championship|1886]], [[1890 British Home Championship|1890]], [[1903 British Home Championship|1903]], [[1906 British Home Championship|1906]], [[1908 British Home Championship|1908]], [[1912 British Home Championship|1912]], [[1927 British Home Championship|1927]], [[1931 British Home Championship|1931]], [[1935 British Home Championship|1935]], [[1939 British Home Championship|1939]], [[1977 British Home Championship|1953]], [[1977 British Home Championship|1956]], [[1977 British Home Championship|1960]], [[1964 British Home Championship|1964]], [[1970 British Home Championship|1970]], [[1972 British Home Championship|1972]], [[1974 British Home Championship|1974]]\n*'''[[Rous Cup]]'''\n**'''''Winners (1)''''': [[1985 Rous Cup|1985]]\n*'''[[Kirin Cup]]'''\n**'''''Winners (1)''''': [[Kirin Cup#2006 Kirin Cup|2006]]\n*'''Qatar Airways Cup'''\n**'''''Winners (1)''''': 2015<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scotlandfootballstats.co.uk/competitions/qatar-airways-cup | title=Qatar Airways Cup | publisher=Scotland Football Stats | accessdate=18 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Stadium==\n{{Main|Scotland national football team home stadium}}\n[[File:Hampden Park WP EN.JPG|thumb|right|[[Hampden Park]], the traditional home of the Scotland national football team. This picture was taken before the [[exhibition game|friendly match]] with the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] in 2005.]]\n[[Hampden Park]] in Glasgow is the traditional home of the Scotland team and is described by the SFA as the National Stadium.<ref>{{cite web | title=Hampden Park | url=http://guide.visitscotland.com/vs/guide/5,en,SCH1/objectId,SPF47918Svs,curr,GBP,season,at1,selectedEntry,home/home.html | publisher=Scottish Tourist Board | accessdate=15 September 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007152159/http://guide.visitscotland.com/vs/guide/5,en,SCH1/objectId,SPF47918Svs,curr,GBP,season,at1,selectedEntry,home/home.html | archivedate=7 October 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The present stadium is one of three stadiums to have used the name. Stadiums named Hampden Park have hosted international matches since 1878. The present site was opened in 1903 and became the primary home ground of the Scotland team from 1906. The attendance record of 149,415 was set by the Scotland v England match in 1937.<ref name=\"hampden\">{{cite web | title=Hampden Park | url= http://www.uefa.com/competitions/uefacup/finals/newsid=511874.html | publisher=UEFA | date=14 March 2007 | accessdate=16 May 2007}}</ref> Safety regulations reduced the capacity to 81,000 by 1977 and the stadium was completely redeveloped during the 1990s, giving the present capacity of 52,000. Hampden is rated as a category four (elite) stadium within the [[UEFA stadium categories]], having previously held the five-star status under the old rating system.<ref>{{cite web | title=Hampden | url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/image_gallery.cfm?page=3089 | publisher=Scottish Football Association | work=www.scottishfa.co.uk | accessdate=17 February 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005170524/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/image_gallery.cfm?page=3089 | archivedate=5 October 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSome [[exhibition game|friendly match]]es are played at smaller venues. [[Pittodrie Stadium]] in [[Aberdeen]] and [[Easter Road Stadium|Easter Road]] in [[Edinburgh]] were both used as venues during the [[2012\u201313 in Scottish football|2012\u201313 season]]. Other stadiums were also used while Hampden was being redeveloped during the 1990s. [[Celtic Park]], [[Ibrox Stadium]], Pittodrie Stadium and [[Rugby Park]] all hosted matches during the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]] qualifying campaign,<ref>{{cite web | title=Scotland&nbsp;\u2013 International Matches 1996\u20132001 | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scot-intres2001.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate=15 September 2008}}</ref> while [[Tynecastle Stadium]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Scotland National Team Match Details | url= http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/match_details.cfm?matchid=57886 | publisher=Scottish Football Association | accessdate=16 May 2007}}</ref> Pittodrie,<ref>{{cite web | title=Scotland National Team Match Details | url= http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/match_details.cfm?matchid=57887 | publisher=Scottish Football Association | accessdate=16 May 2007}}</ref> Celtic Park and Ibrox Stadium were used for [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]] qualifying matches. Since the last redevelopment to Hampden was completed in 1999, Scotland have played most of their competitive matches there. The most recent exception to this rule was in 2014, when Hampden was temporarily converted into an athletics stadium for the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30044407 |title=Scotland: Gordon Strachan hails Celtic Park atmosphere |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 November 2014 |accessdate=14 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Media coverage==\nScotland's home matches are presently covered by the pay-TV broadcaster [[Sky Sports]].<ref name = \"Salmond hits out\">{{cite news | title=Salmond hits out over TV football  | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7267706.stm |publisher=BBC News | date=27 February 2008 | accessdate=4 October 2008}}</ref><ref name = \"2016 and 2018 deal\"/> Television rights to away games vary, although Sky Sports also held the rights to both home and away qualifiers for Euro 2016 and the 2018 World Cup.<ref name = \"2016 and 2018 deal\">{{cite news |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12011/8712153/UEFA-Euro-2016-and-FIFA-2018-World-Cup-qualifiers-live-on-Sky-Sports |title=UEFA Euro 2016 and FIFA 2018 World Cup qualifiers live on Sky Sports |publisher=Sky Sports |date=14 May 2013 |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> The arrangements to show Scotland matches on pay-TV have been criticised by the [[Scottish Government]], who have argued that qualifying matches should be included in the [[Ofcom Code on Sports and Other Listed and Designated Events|list of sporting events]] which can only be broadcast on free-to-air television.<ref name = \"Salmond hits out\"/><ref>{{cite news | title=Scotland games 'should be free' | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/7639315.stm |publisher=BBC News | date=27 September 2008 | accessdate=4 October 2008}}</ref> The SFA have argued that limiting the rights to [[free-to-air]] broadcasters would severely reduce the amount of revenue that they could generate.<ref>{{cite news |  url = http://sport.scotsman.com/scotlandsfootballteam/Smith-fires-a-warning-shot.5494310.jp | title = Smith fires a warning shot to Westminster over Scotland TV rights |work=The Scotsman |publisher=Johnston Publishing | date = 26 July 2009 | accessdate = 13 August 2009}}</ref> An independent advisory panel recommended that qualifying matches played by all four Home Nations be added to the list, but [[Minister for Sport (United Kingdom)|UK Sports Minister]] [[Hugh Robertson (politician)|Hugh Robertson]] deferred a decision until the completion of the [[digital television transition|digital switchover]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-10715529 |title=Scotland games to stay on pay TV |publisher=BBC News |work= |date=21 July 2010 |accessdate=24 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[BBC Scotland]],<ref name = \"Salmond hits out\"/><ref name = \"bbc coverage\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/8918078.stm |title=BBC to screen Scotland away ties on road to Euro 2012 |publisher=BBC Sport |work= |date=16 August 2010 |accessdate=16 August 2010}}</ref> [[STV (TV channel)|STV]], [[Setanta Sports]],<ref name = \"Salmond hits out\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8115360.stm |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |accessdate=16 August 2010 |date=23 June 2009 |title=Setanta goes into administration }}</ref> [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]]<ref>{{cite news | title=Channel 5 Ad Campaign Promoting Scotland v Croatia Coverage | url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2000/oct/10/channelfive.broadcasting |work=The Guardian | date=10 October 2000 | accessdate=9 October 2008 | location=London | first=Jason | last=Deans}}</ref> and [[BT Sport]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/world-cup-qualifier-macedonia-v-scotland-match-preview-8806857.html |title=World Cup qualifier: Macedonia v Scotland match preview  |work=The Independent |publisher= |first=Tom |last=Roddy |date=10 September 2013 |accessdate=12 September 2013 |location=London}}</ref> are among other networks that have previously shown live fixtures. All matches are broadcast with full commentary on [[BBC Radio Scotland]] and, when schedules allow, [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] also.<ref name = \"bbc coverage\"/><ref>{{cite web | title=BBC Radio 5 Live Coverage | url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/fivelive/sport/commentaries.shtml | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080718003547/http://www.bbc.co.uk/fivelive/sport/commentaries.shtml | archivedate= 18 July 2008 |publisher=BBC | date=9 October 2008 | accessdate=9 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Colours==\n[[File:Andrew Watson Footballer.jpg|thumb|right|Scotland players, including [[Andrew Watson (footballer, born 1856)|Andrew Watson]] (top centre), wearing the [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|Rosebery]] colours of primrose and pink in 1882]]\nScotland traditionally wear dark blue shirts with white shorts and dark blue socks, the colours of the [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] team who represented Scotland in the first international.<ref name=\"oldest\" /> The blue Scotland shirt was earlier used in a February 1872 [[rugby union|rugby]] international, with reports stating that \"the scotch were easily distinguishable by their uniform of blue jerseys.... the jerseys having the [[thistle]] embroidered\".<ref>Daily News (London, England), Tuesday, 6 February 1872; Issue 8042.</ref> The thistle had previously been worn to represent Scotland in the 1871 rugby international, but on ''brown'' shirts.<ref>''[[The Herald (Scotland)|Glasgow Herald]]'', 28 March 1871; Issue 9746.</ref> The shirt is embroidered with a crest based upon the lion rampant of the [[Royal Standard of Scotland]].\n{{Football kit box\n|align= left\n|pattern_b  = _sco96\n|pattern_sh = _sco96\n|leftarm    = 000063\n|body       = 000063\n|rightarm   = 000063\n|shorts     = 000063\n|socks      = 000063\t\n|title      = Tartan-style kit with blue shorts worn at [[UEFA Euro 1996]]\n}}\nAnother style often used by Scotland comprises blue shirts, white shorts and red socks. Change colours vary, but are most commonly white or yellow shirts with blue shorts.<ref>{{cite book |last=Devlin |first=John |title=True Colours 2 |publisher=A & C Black |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-7136-7928-1}}</ref> From 1994\u201396 a [[tartan]] kit was used; this kit was worn at [[UEFA Euro 1996]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Scotland | url= http://www.kitclassics.co.uk/Internl.htm | publisher=Kit Classics | accessdate=5 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nScotland have not always played in dark blue; on a number of occasions between 1881 and 1951 they played in the primrose and pink racing colours of [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery]]. A former [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]], Lord Rosebery was an influential figure in Scottish football, serving as honorary President of the SFA and [[Edinburgh]] team [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]]. His colours were used most frequently in the first decade of the 20th century, but were discontinued in 1909. The colours were briefly reprised in 1949, and were last used against [[France national football team|France]] in 1951. In 1900, when Scotland defeated England 4\u20131, Lord Rosebery remarked, \"I have never seen my colours so well sported since [[Ladas (horse)|Ladas]] won the [[Epsom Derby|Derby]]\".<ref name=\"Rosebery\">{{cite web | title=1900 Rosebery Shirt | url= http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football.cfm?curpageid=236 | publisher=Scottish Football Association | accessdate=31 May 2007}}</ref> Rosebery colours were revived as a [[away colours|change kit]] for the [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying]] matches.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/blogs-magazine-monitor-26371625 |title=The beauty/horror of the garish new Scotland away strip |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=27 February 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2014 |first=Steven |last=Brocklehurst}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/feb/26/scotlands-new-away-kit-beckham-glory-days |title=Scotland's away kit: 'A rare occasion, unknown since Beckham's glory days' |first1=John |last1=Ashdown |first2=Hadley |last2=Freeman |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |date=26 February 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe current version of the crest is a roundel similar to the crest used from 1961 to 1988 enclosing a shield, with \"Scotland\" written on the top and \"Est<!--established--> 1873\" on the bottom. In the shield background there are 11 thistles, representing the national flower of Scotland, in addition to the lion rampant. Since 2005, the SFA have supported the use of [[Scottish Gaelic]] on the national team's strip in recognition of the language's revival in Scotland.<ref>{{cite news | title=Gaelic added to Scotland strips | publisher=BBC News |work= | date=24 August 2006 | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/highlands_and_islands/5282936.stm | accessdate=31 August 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Supporters==\n{{Main|Tartan Army}}\n[[File:Tartan Army.png|thumb|The Tartan Army in Milan in 2005, prior to their [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification&nbsp;\u2013 UEFA Group 5|2006 World Cup qualifying]] match against [[Italy national football team|Italy]]]]\nScotland fans are collectively known as the [[Tartan Army]]. During the 1970s, Scotland fans became known for their [[football hooligan|hooliganism]] in England, particularly after they [[pitch invasion|invaded]] the [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]] pitch and destroyed the goalposts after the England v Scotland match in 1977.<ref name=\"tartan2\">{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Adrian |author2=& Porter, Dilwyn (eds.) |title=Sport and National Identity in the Post-War World |publisher=Routledge |year=2004 |isbn=0-415-28300-0}} p77</ref> Since then, the Tartan Army have won awards from [[UEFA]] for their combination of vocal support, friendly nature and charity work.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Tartan Army | url= http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football.cfm?curpageid=1205 | publisher=Scottish Football Association | accessdate=11 April 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Tartan Army Sunshine Appeal | url= http://www.tasunshineappeal.co.uk/ | publisher=Tartan Army Sunshine Appeal | accessdate=16 May 2007}}</ref> The Tartan Army have been awarded a [[Sportsmanship|Fair Play]] prize by the [[Belgium at the Olympics|Belgian Olympic Committee]]<ref name=\"t-army\">{{cite news | title=Tartan Army wins fair play award | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/1682841.stm |publisher=BBC Sport | date=29 November 2001 |accessdate=16 May 2007}}</ref> and were named as the best supporters during the [[1992 UEFA European Championship|1992 European Championship]].<ref name=\"t-army\" /> The fans were also presented with a trophy for non-violence in sport and were voted by journalists to be the best supporters for their sense of fair play and sporting spirit at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]] in France.<ref>{{cite web | title=World Cup&nbsp;\u2013 France 1998 | url= http://www.t-army.com/tar_hool.html | publisher= t-army.com | accessdate=12 June 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070818131232/http://www.t-army.com/tar_hool.html |archivedate = 18 August 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Players==\n{{See also|List of Scotland international footballers|List of Scotland international footballers (5\u201324 caps)|List of Scotland international footballers (1\u20134 caps)|List of Scotland international footballers born outside Scotland}}\n\n===Current squad===\nThe following players were called up for the [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying]] matches against [[Cyprus national football team|Cyprus]] and [[Kazakhstan national football team|Kazakhstan]] in November 2019.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=ScotlandNT |number=1191681587664035842 |date=5 November 2019 |accessdate=5 November 2019 |title=Steve Clarke has named his Scotland squad to face Cyprus and Kazakhstan later this month.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50296744 |title=Scotland: Arsenal requested Kieran Tierney omission, says Steve Clarke |first=Heather |last=Dewar |website=BBC Sport |date=5 November 2019 |accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/scotland/50389854 |title=Scotland: Andy Robertson, Ryan Fraser and Scott McTominay withdraw from squad |website=BBC Sport |date=12 November 2019 |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=ScotlandNT |number=1194313436748013569 |date=12 November 2019 |accessdate=12 November 2019 |title=Scotland squad update}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=ScotlandNT |number=1196110788194377728 |date=17 November 2019 |accessdate=17 November 2019 |title=Scotland squad 