nsas City]]|clubnat=USA|latest={{dts|13 October 2019}}, v. {{fb|SMR}}}}\n{{nat fs r player|no= |pos=FW|name=[[Matt Phillips]]|sortname=Phillips, Matt|age={{birth date and age|1991|3|13|df=y}}|caps=16|goals=1|club=[[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]|clubnat=ENG|latest={{dts|9 September 2019}}, v. {{fb|BEL}}}}\n{{nat fs r player|no= |pos=FW|name=[[Marc McNulty]]|sortname=McNulty, Marc|age={{birth date and age|1992|9|14|df=y}}|caps=2|goals=0|club=[[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]]|clubnat=SCO|latest={{dts|11 June 2019}}, v. {{fb|BEL}}}}\n{{nat fs break}}\n<sup>RET</sup> Player has announced retirement from international football.<br/>\n{{nat fs end}}\n\n===Honoured players===\nThe [[Scottish Football Association]] operates a [[Scotland national football team roll of honour|roll of honour]] for every player who has made more than 50 appearances for Scotland.<ref name=\"roll of honour\">{{cite web|title=International Roll of Honour |publisher=[[Scottish Football Association]] |url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football_players.cfm?page=138 |accessdate=9 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011104402/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football_players.cfm?page=138 |archivedate=11 October 2010 }}</ref> {{As of|2017|November}} there are 31 members of this roll,<ref name = \"roll of honour\"/> with [[Craig Gordon]] the most recent addition to the list. The qualifying mark of 50 appearances means that many notable Scotland players including [[Jim Baxter]], [[Hughie Gallacher]], [[John Greig]], [[Jimmy Johnstone]], [[Billy McNeill]], [[Bobby Murdoch]], [[Archie Gemmill]] and [[Lawrie Reilly]] are not on the roll of honour.\n\nThe [[Scottish Football Museum]] operates a [[Scottish Football Hall of Fame|hall of fame]] which is open to players and managers involved in [[football in Scotland|Scottish football]]. This means that membership is not restricted to people who have played for Scotland; inductees include [[Brian Laudrup]] and [[Henrik Larsson]]. At the most recent induction ceremony, [[Alan Rough]], [[Martin Buchan]], [[Eddie Gray (footballer, born 1948)|Eddie Gray]], [[Tommy Docherty]], [[Scot Symon]] and [[Bobby Walker (footballer, born 1879)|Bobby Walker]] were added to its membership.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scottish Football Hall of Fame Dinner 2013, Celebrating 10 years of the Scottish Football Hall of Fame|url=http://www.scottishfootballmuseum.org.uk/hall-of-fame/2013.html|work=Scottish Football Museum|accessdate=15 November 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110230226/http://www.scottishfootballmuseum.org.uk/hall-of-fame/2013.html|archivedate=10 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Sportscotland]] operates the [[Scottish Sports Hall of Fame]], which has [[Scottish Sports Hall of Fame#Football|inducted some footballers]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sporting legends honoured in Scottish Sports Hall of Fame|url=http://www.sportscotland.org.uk/news/sportscotland/newsarchive/2012/sporting_legends_honoured_in_scottish_sports_hall_of_fame/|accessdate=14 October 2015|publisher=Sportscotland|date=13 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304042828/http://www.sportscotland.org.uk/news/sportscotland/newsarchive/2012/sporting_legends_honoured_in_scottish_sports_hall_of_fame/|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Managers==\n{{main|Scotland national football team manager}}\nFrom 1872 to 1953, and 1954 to 1957, the Scotland national team was appointed by a selection committee. [[Andy Beattie]] was manager for six matches in 1954 when Scotland competed at their first World Cup. After the tournament the selection committee resumed their duties, continuing until the appointment of [[Matt Busby]] in 1958. Busby was initially unable to assume his duties due to the serious injuries he sustained in the [[Munich air disaster]].<ref name = \"wsc 1958\"/>\n\nStatistically the most successful manager was [[Alex McLeish]], who won seven of the ten games during his first spell as manager. Discounting managers who took charge of less than ten games, the least successful manager was [[George Burley]], with just three wins in 14 games.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Scotland career\n!Played\n!Won\n!Drawn\n!Lost\n!Win %\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|Selection committee\n|1872\u20131953\n{{WDL|231\n|139\n|42\n|50}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Andy|Beattie}}\n|1954\n{{WDL|6\n|2\n|1\n|3}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|Selection committee\n|1954\u20131957\n{{WDL|23\n|10\n|7\n|6}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Dawson|Walker}}<ref group=\"note\">Dawson Walker was left in charge of the players due to the Munich air disaster, in which official manager Matt Busby was seriously injured.</ref>\n|1958\n{{WDL|6\n|1\n|2\n|3}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Matt|Busby}}\n|1958\n{{WDL|2\n|1\n|1\n|0}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Andy|Beattie}}\n|1959\u20131960\n{{WDL|12\n|3\n|3\n|6}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Ian|McColl}}\n|1960\u20131965\n{{WDL|28\n|17\n|3\n|8}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Jock|Stein}}\n|1965\u20131966\n{{WDL|7\n|3\n|1\n|3}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|John|Prentice|dab=footballer, born 1926}}\n|1966\n{{WDL|4\n|0\n|1\n|3}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Malky|McDonald}}<ref name = \"caretaker\" group=\"note\"/>\n|1966\u20131967\n{{WDL|2\n|1\n|1\n|0}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Bobby|Brown|dab=footballer, born 1923}}\n|1967\u20131971\n{{WDL|28\n|9\n|8\n|11}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Tommy|Docherty}}\n|1971\u20131972\n{{WDL|12\n|7\n|2\n|3}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Willie|Ormond}}\n|1973\u20131977\n{{WDL|38\n|18\n|8\n|12}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Ally|MacLeod}}\n|1977\u20131978\n{{WDL|17\n|7\n|5\n|5}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Jock|Stein}}\n|1978\u20131985\n{{WDL|61\n|26\n|12\n|23}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Alex|Ferguson}}<ref group=\"note\">Alex Ferguson was interim manager, following the death of Jock Stein.</ref>\n|1985\u20131986\n{{WDL|10\n|3\n|4\n|3}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Andy|Roxburgh}}\n|1986\u20131993\n{{WDL|61\n|23\n|19\n|19}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Craig|Brown|dab=footballer, born 1940}}\n|1993\u20132002\n{{WDL|71\n|32\n|18\n|21}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Berti|Vogts}}\n|2002\u20132004\n{{WDL|32\n|9\n|7\n|16}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Tommy|Burns|dab=footballer}}<ref name = \"caretaker\" group=\"note\"/>\n|2004\n{{WDL|1\n|0\n|0\n|1\n}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Walter|Smith}}\n|2004\u20132007\n{{WDL|16\n|7\n|5\n|4}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Alex|McLeish}}\n|2007\n{{WDL|10\n|7\n|0\n|3}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|George|Burley}}\n|2008\u20132009\n{{WDL|14\n|3\n|3\n|8}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Craig|Levein}}\n|2009\u20132012\n{{WDL|24\n|10\n|5\n|9}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Billy|Stark}}<ref name = \"caretaker\" group=\"note\">Served as manager on a caretaker basis.</ref>\n|2012\n{{WDL|1\n|1\n|0\n|0}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Gordon|Strachan}}\n|2013\u20132017\n{{WDL|40\n|19\n|9\n|12}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Malky|Mackay}}<ref name = \"caretaker\" group=\"note\"/>\n|2017\n{{WDL|1\n|0\n|0\n|1}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Alex|McLeish}}\n|2018\u20132019\n{{WDL|12\n|5\n|0\n|7}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{sortname|Steve|Clarke}}\n|2019\u2013present\n{{WDL|8\n|4\n|0\n|4}}\n|-\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! colspan=\"2\"|Totals\n{{WDLtot|778|367|167|244}}\n|}\n<small>Last updated: Scotland v Kazakhstan, 19 November 2019. Statistics include official FIFA-recognised matches, and a match against a [[Hong Kong League XI]] played on 23 May 2002 that the [[Scottish Football Association]] includes in its statistical totals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international_fixture_details.cfm?page=1921&matchID=28324 |title=Hong Kong v Scotland |work=www.scottishfa.co.uk |publisher=Scottish Football Association |accessdate=19 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_manager_profile.cfm?page=1921&managerID=35&squadID=1 |title=Gordon Strachan |work=www.scottishfa.co.uk |publisher=Scottish Football Association |accessdate=19 September 2013}}</ref></small>\n\n==Records==\n{{Main|Scotland national football team records}}\n[[File:Kenny_Dalglish_2009_Singapore.jpg|thumb|[[Kenny Dalglish]] scored a joint record 30 goals in a record 102 international appearances for Scotland between 1971 and 1986.]]\n[[Kenny Dalglish]] holds the record for Scotland appearances, having played 102 times between 1971 and 1986. He is the only Scotland player to have reached 100 [[cap (sport)|caps]].<ref name = \"roll of honour\"/> [[Jim Leighton]] is second, having played 91 times, a Scottish record for appearances by a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]].<ref name = \"roll of honour\"/> The title of Scotland's highest goalscorer is shared by two players. [[Denis Law]] scored 30 goals between 1958 and 1974, during which time he played for Scotland on 55 occasions. [[Kenny Dalglish]] scored an equal number from 102 appearances. [[Hughie Gallacher]] as well as being the third highest scorer is also the most prolific with his 24 goals coming from only 20 games (averaging 1.2 goals per game).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://qosfc.com/news-3313|title=QosFC: Hughie Gallacher goals for Scotland|website=qosfc.com}}</ref>\n\nThe largest margin of victory achieved by a Scotland side is 11\u20130 against [[Ireland national football team (IFA)|Ireland]] in the [[1901 British Home Championship]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Scotland&nbsp;\u2013 International Matches 1901\u20131910 | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scot-intres1910.html | publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation | date= 6 June 2008 | accessdate=1 September 2007}}</ref> The record defeat occurred during the [[1954 FIFA World Cup]], a 7\u20130 deficit against reigning world champions [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]].<ref>{{cite web| title=World Cup | url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/image_gallery.cfm?page=3123 | publisher=Scottish Football Association |work=www.scottishfa.co.uk |accessdate=17 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nScotland's [[1937 British Home Championship]] match against England set a new world record for a football attendance. The Hampden Park crowd was officially recorded as 149,415, though the true figure is unknown as a large number of additional fans gained unauthorised entry. This attendance was surpassed 13 years later by the [[Uruguay v Brazil (1950 FIFA World Cup)|decisive match]] of the [[1950 FIFA World Cup]], but remains a European record.<ref>{{cite web | last==Coates |first=Jonathan | title=The day Hampden Park sat on top of the world | url= http://heritage.scotsman.com/top-stories/The-day-Hampden-Park-sat.3276773.jp?CommentPage=1&CommentPageLength=1000 |work=The Scotsman | date=14 April 2007 | accessdate=17 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=McLeish: We can be heroes | url= https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/news/newsid=638588.html | publisher=FIFA.com | date=16 November 2007 | accessdate=17 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n==United Kingdom team==\n{{Main|United Kingdom national football team|Great Britain Olympic football team}}\n\nScotland has always participated by itself in most of the major tournaments, such as the [[FIFA World Cup]] and the [[UEFA European Championship]]. At the [[Olympic Games]] the [[International Olympic Committee]] charter only permit a [[Great Britain Olympic football team]], representing the whole of the United Kingdom, to compete.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/may/21/scotland.london|title=Salmond aims for Scottish Olympic gold|work=The Guardian|publisher= Guardian News and Media Limited|first=Dan|last=Bell|date= 21 May 2007|accessdate=4 September 2011|location=London}}</ref> Teams of amateur players represented [[Great Britain at the Olympics]] from 1900 until 1972, but the FA stopped entering a team after then because the distinction between amateur and professional was abolished. The [[London 2012 Olympic bid|successful bid]] by London for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] prompted the FA to explore how a team could be entered.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/olympics_2012/4657649.stm|title=FA wants GB team in 2012 Olympics |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 July 2005|accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> The SFA responded by stating that it would not participate, as it feared that this would threaten the independent status of the Scotland national team.<ref>{{cite news | title=No Scots for GB Olympic football | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/4426566.stm |publisher=BBC Sport | date=11 November 2005 | accessdate=11 April 2007}}</ref> [[President of FIFA|FIFA President]] [[Sepp Blatter]] denied this,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4206540.stm | title=Smith 'excited' by Olympic team |publisher=BBC Sport | date=2 September 2005 | accessdate=8 January 2008}}</ref> but the SFA expressed concern that a future President could take a different view. An agreement was reached in May 2009 whereby the FA would be permitted to organise a team using only England-qualified players,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympic_games/8072981.stm |title=Nations pave way for 2012 GB team |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 May 2009 |accessdate=5 January 2010}}</ref> but this was successfully challenged by the [[British Olympic Association]]. Only English and Welsh players were selected for the men's squad,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/football/9369976/London-2012-Olympics-Stuart-Pearce-names-Team-GB-football-squad.html |title=London 2012 Olympics: Stuart Pearce names Team GB football squad |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |publisher= |date=2 July 2012 |accessdate=17 November 2019 |first=Paul |last=Kelso}}</ref> but two Scottish players were selected for the [[Great Britain women's Olympic football team|women's team]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/football/9356444/London-2012-Olympics-Hope-Powell-names-first-ever-Team-GB-womens-football-squad-for-Games.html| work=Daily Telegraph | title=London 2012 Olympics: Hope Powell names first-ever Team GB women's football squad for Games| date=26 June 2012|accessdate=26 June 2012|first=Alice|last=Philipson}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Portal|Scotland|Association football}}\n<references group=\"note\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Scotland national association football team}}\n* [http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/ Scottish Football Association]\n* [http://www.fitbastats.com/scotland/index.php Complete results and player statistics] at ''FitbaStats''\n\n{{Scotland national football team}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Squads\n|titlestyle=background:#003876;color:#ffffff; \n|list1=\n{{Scotland squad 1954 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Scotland squad 1958 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Scotland squad 1974 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Scotland squad 1978 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Scotland squad 1982 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Scotland squad 1986 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Scotland squad 1990 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Scotland squad UEFA Euro 1992}}\n{{Scotland squad UEFA Euro 1996}}\n{{Scotland squad 1998 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Finalists\n|titlestyle=background:#003876;color:#ffffff; \n|list1=\n{{UEFA Euro 1992 finalists}}\n{{UEFA Euro 1996 finalists}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes|titlestyle=background:#003876;color:#ffffff;\n|list1=\n{{Football in Scotland}}\n{{Football in the United Kingdom}}\n{{UEFA teams}}\n{{National sports teams of Scotland}}\n{{SFWA Footballer of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scotland National Football Team}}\n[[Category:Scotland national football team| ]]\n[[Category:European national association football teams]]\n[[Category:National sports teams of Scotland|Football]]\n[[Category:1872 establishments in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "DisambiguateEaster RoadtoEaster Road Stadiumusingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scotland_national_football_team"}
{"title_page": "Speed Freak Killers", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name        = Loren Herzog\n| image       = Loren Herzog.jpg\n| caption     = Mugshot\n| alt         = \n| birthname   = Loren Joseph Herzog\n| alias       = The Speed Freak Killer\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1965|12|8|mf=y}}<ref>California Births, 1905 - 1995, [http://www.familytreelegends.com/records/39461?c=search&first=Loren&last=Herzog Loren J. Herzog]</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Linden, California]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2012|1|16|1965|12|8|mf=y}}<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.mercurynews.com/2012/03/06/speed-freak-killers-cause-of-death-deep-anger-revealed/ |title=Speed Freak Killer's cause of death, deep anger revealed |work=The Mercury News |date=March 6, 2012 |accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref>\n| death_place = [[Susanville, California]], U.S.\n| cause       = [[Suicide]]\n| conviction  = [[Murder]] (4 counts, overturned)<br>[[Voluntary manslaughter]]<br>[[Accessory (legal term)|Accessory]] to [[murder]] (3 counts)<br>Furnishing [[amphetamine]]\n| sentence    = 78 years (overturned)<br>\n14 years, paroled after 11 years\n| victims     = 3\u201319<ref name=\"CBS News\">{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-201_162-57562673/fbi-digging-up-calif-well-looking-for-more-speed-freak-killers-victims/ | work=CBS News | title=FBI digging up Calif. well looking for more \"Speed Freak Killers\" victims}}</ref>\n| beginyear   = 1984\n| endyear     = 1999\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| states      = [[California]]\n| apprehended = March 17, 1999\n}}\n\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name        = Wesley Shermantine\n| image       = Wesley Shermantine.jpg\n| image_size  = 200px\n| caption     = 2007 San Quentin State Prison mugshot\n| alt         = \n| birthname   = Wesley Howard Shermantine, Jr.\n| alias       = The Speed Freak Killer\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1966|2|24|mf=y}}<ref>California Births, 1905 - 1995, http://www.familytreelegends.com/records/39461?c=search&first=Wesley&last=Shermantine Wesley H. Shermantine</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Linden, California]], U.S.\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| cause       = \n| conviction  = [[Murder]]\n| sentence    = [[Death penalty]]\n| victims     = 4\u201319<ref name=\"CBS News\">{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-201_162-57562673/fbi-digging-up-calif-well-looking-for-more-speed-freak-killers-victims/ | work=CBS News | title=FBI digging up Calif. well looking for more \"Speed Freak Killers\" victims}}</ref> \n| beginyear   = 1984\n| endyear     = 1999\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| states      = [[California]], [[Utah]]\n| apprehended = March 17, 1999\n}}\n\nThe '''Speed Freak Killers''' is the name given to [[serial killer]] duo '''Loren Herzog''' and '''Wesley Shermantine''', together initially convicted of four murders \u2014 three jointly \u2014 and suspected in the deaths of as many as 72 people in and around [[San Joaquin County, California]]. They received the \"speed freak\" moniker due to their [[methamphetamine]] abuse.\n\nHerzog committed suicide in 2012. {{As of|2016}} Shermantine remains on [[death row]] in [[San Quentin State Prison]], in [[San Quentin, California]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Map by 'Speed Freak Killer' Wesley Shermantine leads cops to 300 human bones |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/map-by-speed-freak-killer-wesley-shermantine-leads-cops-to-300-human-bones/ |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=CBSNews.com |date=February 13, 2012 |access-date=October 7, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-serialkiller-20120213,0,2221324.story |url-status=dead |work=Los Angeles Times |first=Diana |last=Marcum |title='Speed Freak' killer's disclosures bring both peace and turmoil |date=February 13, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213212726/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-serialkiller-20120213,0,2221324.story |archivedate=February 13, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nHerzog and Shermantine grew up as childhood friends in the town of [[Linden, California]]. The citizens of Linden, a small town with fewer than 2,000 people, 95 miles east of [[San Francisco]], were long aware of the duo's reputation as methamphetamine users. They were regulars at the Linden Inn, a bar owned by the father of 25-year-old Cyndi Vanderheiden of [[Clements, California]]. Vanderheiden went missing after leaving the Linden Inn with Herzog and Shermantine on November 14, 1998.\n\nInvestigation into Vanderheiden's disappearance was ongoing into 1999, and Shermantine was the prime suspect.  In mid-January 1999, Shermantine's car was repossessed, and was subsequently searched by the [[San Joaquin County, California|San Joaquin]] Sheriff's Department. Blood identified as being from Cyndi Vanderheiden was discovered in the car, and while [[DNA]] test results were being confirmed, the sheriff's department focused on Loren Herzog, Shermantine's friend and suspected accomplice. He was extensively questioned.\n\nHerzog described when Shermantine shot a hunter they ran into while they were on vacation in Utah in 1994. Utah police confirmed that a hunter was shot to death, but his murder was still classified as unsolved. Herzog also said Shermantine was responsible for killing Henry Howell, who was found parked off the road on Highway 88 in Alpine County with his teeth and head bashed in.  Herzog said he and Shermantine passed Howell parked on the highway and Shermantine stopped, grabbed Howell's shotgun, killed him, and stole what little money he had. Additionally, Herzog gave specific details about how Shermantine killed Robin Armtrout.\n\nHerzog and Shermantine both were arrested by the [[San Joaquin County Sheriff's Department]] and charged with several counts of murder each in March 1999.\n\n== 2001 convictions ==\nIn 2001, a jury found Shermantine guilty of four murders: those of Vanderheiden, Howard King and Paul Cavanaugh&nbsp;\u2013 each shot dead in his car in 1984, and 16-year-old Chevelle \"Chevy\" Wheeler, who disappeared in 1985 from [[Franklin High School (Stockton, California)|Franklin High School]] in [[Stockton, California|Stockton]] after telling friends she was leaving school to go with Shermantine to his family's cabin in [[San Andreas, California|San Andreas]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-504083_162-57379366-504083/speed-freak-killers-update-search-for-victims-remains-reaches-bottom-of-calif-well/ | work=CBS News | title='Speed Freak Killers' Update: Search for victims' remains reaches bottom of Calif. well}}</ref> Shermantine was sentenced to death and is on death row at [[San Quentin State Prison]].\n\nHerzog was charged with five counts of murder in 1999: that of Cyndi Vanderheiden, Henry Howell, Paul Raymond Cavanaugh, Howard Michael King III, and Roberta \"Robin\" Ray Armtrout.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Four additional murder counts filed against Loren Herzog|url = http://www.lodinews.com/news/article_71ee4b7c-379c-11e4-9987-001a4bcf887a.html|website = Lodinews.com|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref> In his 2001 trial, a jury found him guilty on three murder counts (Vanderheiden, Cavanaugh, and King), the lesser charge of accessory to murder in the Howell count, and [[Acquittal|acquitted]] him on the Armtrout count.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Jury finds Herzog guilty|url = http://www.recordnet.com/article/20011024/A_NEWS/310249967|website = recordnet.com|access-date = February 20, 2016|first = Linda Hughes-Kirchubel Record Staff|last = Writer}}</ref> Herzog was given a 78-year sentence.\n\n== Appeals and overturned convictions ==\nAn appeals court overturned all of Herzog's convictions in August 2004, after ruling that three of Herzog's four confessions were coerced.<ref name=\"lodinews.com\">{{Cite web|title = Convicted killer Loren Herzog commits suicide|url = http://www.lodinews.com/news/article_64587e42-4122-11e1-b68e-001871e3ce6c.html|website = Lodinews.com|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref> In the case of the fourth, that of Cyndi Vanderheiden, a retrial was ordered. This retrial never took place. Rather, a plea bargain was reached, where Herzog pleaded guilty to voluntary manslaughter and furnishing amphetamine in the Vanderheiden case, and to being an accessory to murder in the Cavanaugh, King, and Howell cases. Accordingly, Herzog's sentence was reduced to 14 years, with credit for six years served.<ref name=\"lodinews.com\"/> With credit off his sentence for good behavior, Herzog served 11 years in prison and was in a position where he was to be paroled by 2010.\n\nOpposition to the inevitability of Herzog's parole was extremely vocal, especially from victims' families.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Paroled killer Loren Herzog found hanged in his trailer at prison|url = http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/01/loren-herzog-hanged-trailer.html|website = LA Times Blogs - L.A. NOW|date = January 17, 2012|access-date = February 20, 2016|language = en-US}}</ref> That no California county wanted to take him for parole led the California Department of Corrections to parole him to a trailer stationed outside the front gate of the [[High Desert State Prison (California)|High Desert State Prison]] in [[Susanville, California]] in Lassen County in September 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Lassen County loses Herzog parole appeal|url = http://www.recordnet.com/article/20120314/A_NEWS/203140323|website = recordnet.com|access-date = February 20, 2016|first = Scott|last = Smith}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Loren Herzog, Half of \"Speed Freak Killers\" Duo, to be Freed on Parole|url = http://www.cbsnews.com/news/loren-herzog-half-of-speed-freak-killers-duo-to-be-freed-on-parole/|website = www.cbsnews.com|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHerzog committed suicide in January 2012, hanging himself inside his trailer.<ref name=\":0\" /> He did so shortly after [[bounty hunter]] [[Leonard Padilla]] informed Herzog that Shermantine was planning to disclose the location of a well and two other locations where the duo buried their victims. Previously, none of their victims' bodies had been found. Both men maintained that the other did the killing in all cases.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/18/us/serial-killers-graveyard-opens-california-towns-wounds.html | work=The New York Times | first=Malia | last=Wollan | title=Serial Killers' Graveyard Opens California Town's Wounds | date=February 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Discovery of victims' remains==\n\n=== Linden, California well ===\nIn February 2010, while Wesley Shermantine waited on death row, his sister Barbara received letters from him identifying the locations of victims in an abandoned well on Flood Road, near [[Linden, California]]. She turned these letters over to the San Joaquin County Sheriff's Department. The Sheriff's Department followed up on the lead, but in an interview with the property owner, the owner stated that the wells in question were sealed before the victims disappeared. No further action was taken at that time.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Speed Freak Killer's Sister Says Police 'Dropped The Ball' On Her Tips|url = http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2012/10/26/speed-freak-killers-sister-nothing-is-getting-done/|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMore came out in February 2012, based on the promise bounty hunter Leonard Padilla made to Shermantine to pay $33,000 for information.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = Bodies of murder victims found after their killer draws maps for bounty hunter from his death row cell|url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2099654/Wesley-Shermantine-Bodies-murder-victims-killer-draws-maps-death-row-cell.html|website = Mail Online|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref> A map drawn by Shermantine and additional information given again led authorities to the same Linden, California well site he mentioned in 2010. More than 1,000 human bone fragments were recovered. The bones were to be tested by the [[California Department of Justice]] for [[DNA profiling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2012/02/17/speed-freak-killer-speaks-out-in-letter-search-enters-2nd-week/|title='Speed Freak Killer' Speaks Out In Letter, Search Enters 2nd Week|work=cbslocal.com|accessdate=December 12, 2014}}</ref> In March 2012, the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]]'s Evidence Recovery Team was asked to assist with the overall investigation, in part because of how the excavation of the Linden well was handled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2012/03/02/breaking-fbi-now-assisting-in-search-for-victims-of-speed-freak-killers/|title=FBI Asked To Assist In Search For Victims Of 'Speed Freak Killers' \u00ab CBS Sacramento|work=cbslocal.com|accessdate=December 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe identity of the remains recovered in the well were announced to the public on March 30, 2012. They were those of two Stockton, California teens missing since the mid-1980s: Kimberly Ann Billy, 19, who disappeared December 11, 1984 and Joann Hobson, 16, who disappeared August 29, 1985. The remains of an additional victim as well as an unidentified fetus were found in the well.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Two Victims From Linden Well Identified In 'Speed Freak Killers' Case|url = http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2012/03/30/two-victims-from-linden-well-identified-in-speed-freak-killers-case/|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Former Shermantine property ===\nTwo separate burial sites in [[Calaveras County, California]] were also investigated in February 2012 based on a letter Shermantine wrote to Padilla that detailed possible locations of victims.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|title=Coverage Of Shermantine Property Search|url=http://www.kcra.com/slideshow/news/30508345/detail.html|work=KCRA 3|publisher=KCRA-TV|accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref> Shermantine indicated sites nearby property formerly owned by Shermantine's parents.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\"/> Bodies from these two sites were recovered and identified as those of Chevelle \"Chevy\" Wheeler and Cyndi Vanderheiden.\n\n=== September 2012 burial sites ===\nShermantine was briefly released from death row into police custody in September 2012, to lead authorities to four additional abandoned wells where he stated more victim remains would be found, all near the town of Linden, done because he was paid $28,000 by Leonard Padilla.<ref>{{Cite web|title = 'Speed Freak Killer' on death row leads police to remains of victims he murdered decades ago|url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2197327/Wesley-Shermantine-Speed-Freak-Killer-leads-police-remains-victims-murdered-decades-ago.html|website = Mail Online|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref> In early January 2013 the FBI began excavation of a well site, which they hoped would yield more victims' remains.<ref name=\"CBS News\">{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-201_162-57562673/fbi-digging-up-calif-well-looking-for-more-speed-freak-killers-victims/ | work=CBS News | title=FBI digging up Calif. well looking for more \"Speed Freak Killers\" victims}}</ref> Shermantine declined to speak further to authorities. On February 22, 2013, the FBI announced that it had ended the search for victims based on Shermantine's information. Two sites he had indicated had turned up nothing, and \"other directions from him were misguided\".<ref>{{Cite web|title = Search For Victims Of 'Speed Freak Killers' At An End|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/02/22/speed-freak-killers-victim-search-ends-fbi_n_2741017.html|website = The Huffington Post|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShermantine also claimed to know the locations in the [[Lake County, California#National protected areas|Cow Mountain Recreation Area]] of bodies of victims killed by other death row inmates. [[Lake County, California|Lake County]] sheriffs were skeptical that any bodies could be successfully recovered in the large park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/crime-courts/ci_21154679/speed-freak-killer-hints-at-14-bodies-near|title='Speed freak killer' hints at 14 bodies near Clear Lake|work=mercurynews.com|accessdate=December 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Allegations of investigation-hampering==\nSince 2012, several victims' families and elected officials have alleged that the San Joaquin County Sheriff's Office (SJCSO) interfered with and deliberately hampered the continued search for additional possible victims of the \"Speed Freak Killers\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2015/03/14/speed-freak-killers-case-retired-fbi-agent-alleges-san-joaquin-sheriffs-office-sabotaged-crime-scene/|title=Speed Freak Killers case: Retired FBI agent alleges San Joaquin Sheriff's Office sabotaged crime scene|date=March 14, 2015|work=The Mercury News|access-date=October 8, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\nIn 2010, Shermantine wrote a letter to [[California State Senate|California State Senator]] [[Cathleen Galgiani]]\u2014whose cousin, 19-year-old Dena McHan, disappeared in 1981\u2014revealing the locations of the remains of additional victims.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.lodinews.com/news/article_6e77031e-c69c-11e4-a329-cf3a23ed6e47.html?mode=jqm|title=State Sen. Cathleen Galgiani: 'Speed Freak Killers' records deleted|work=Lodinews.com|access-date=October 7, 2018}}</ref> In 2012, Galgiani sponsored the use of taxpayer funds to search for additional victims of the pair, and sought to simplify protocol granting incarcerated persons like Shermantine permission to participate in search excursions.<ref name=\":4\" /> Galgiani turned the letter over to law enforcement and later alleged that missing persons records related to the \"Speed Freak Killers\" case had been deleted, hampering further investigation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sfgate.com/crime/article/Claim-Speed-Freak-Killers-investigators-impeded-6125947.php|title=Speed Freak Killers investigators stymied kidnap probe, suit says|date=March 10, 2015|work=SFGate|access-date=October 8, 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn 2014, the mother of a missing woman filed suit against the SJCSO for mishandling the remains found in the Linden well.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-speed-freak-killers-case-lands-in-federal-court-2014jan10-story.html|title=Mom says county 'pulverized' Calif. girl's remains|last=Press|first=SCOTT SMITH Associated|work=sandiegouniontribune.com|access-date=October 8, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2015, a retired FBI agent corroborated her claims, alleging that the SJCSO deliberately used a backhoe to dig up remains, mangling them to prevent identification, so that the absence of certain files would not be discovered.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 2018, the Sheriff-elect of San Joaquin County announced that the \"Speed Freak Killers\" case would be re-opened.<ref>{{Citation|last=Meza|first=Melinda|title=Sheriff-elect reopens Speed-Freak killers case in San Joaquin County|url=https://www.kcra.com/article/sheriff-elect-reopens-speed-freak-killers-case-in-san-joaquin-county/23015783|language=en|access-date=October 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==In popular media ==\nThis case was featured on episode 178 of the series ''[[American Justice]]'', \"Vanished\", which first aired September 4, 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|title = American Justice|url = http://www.tv.com/shows/american-justice/episodes/|website = TV.com|access-date = February 20, 2016|last = TV.com}}</ref> With the episode's 2002 production date, newer details relating to this case were not a part of the program. Two of the victims' families (the Wheelers and Vanderheidens) did not yet know where their daughters' bodies were, and Herzog was (still) serving a 78-year sentence.\n\nThe story was covered on the 2015 episode [[On the Case with Paula Zahn#ep145|\u201cWhere Evil Lies\u201d]], on the crime documentary series ''[[On the Case with Paula Zahn]]''. The episode included updates on Herzog\u2019s release and suicide, and the discovery of victims\u2019 remains, including Wheeler and Vanderheiden&mdash;with comments from Wheeler\u2018s and Vanderheiden\u2019s families.\n\nIn April 2020 this case is being covered in depth on the popular True Crime podcast, Foul Play. The season is called, the Maps. Each episode the hosts, Shane Waters and Wendy C are taking you through the timeline of events in this case, covering all the twists and turns that happened before and after the trials, and speaking to family members, media representatives and law enforcement, to give you the most up to date information on this case.  https://www.itsfoulplay.com/\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of serial killers in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/serial_killers/partners/speed-freak-killers/an-outraged-community.html \"The Speed Freak Killers\", extensive reportage by Gary C. King, TruTV site]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Speed Freak Killers}}\n[[Category:American serial killers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by California]]\n[[Category:2012 in California]]\n[[Category:2001 in California]]\n[[Category:People from Linden, California]]\n[[Category:Methamphetamine in the United States]]\n[[Category:Criminal duos]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name        = Loren Herzog\n| image       = Loren Herzog.jpg\n| caption     = Mugshot\n| alt         = \n| birthname   = Loren Joseph Herzog\n| alias       = The Speed Freak Killer\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1965|12|8|mf=y}}<ref>California Births, 1905 - 1995, [http://www.familytreelegends.com/records/39461?c=search&first=Loren&last=Herzog Loren J. Herzog]</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Linden, California]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2012|1|16|1965|12|8|mf=y}}<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.mercurynews.com/2012/03/06/speed-freak-killers-cause-of-death-deep-anger-revealed/ |title=Speed Freak Killer's cause of death, deep anger revealed |work=The Mercury News |date=March 6, 2012 |accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref>\n| death_place = [[Susanville, California]], U.S.\n| cause       = [[Suicide]]\n| conviction  = [[Murder]] (4 counts, overturned)<br>[[Voluntary manslaughter]]<br>[[Accessory (legal term)|Accessory]] to [[murder]] (3 counts)<br>Furnishing [[amphetamine]]\n| sentence    = 78 years (overturned)<br>\n14 years, paroled after 11 years\n| victims     = 3\u201319<ref name=\"CBS News\">{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-201_162-57562673/fbi-digging-up-calif-well-looking-for-more-speed-freak-killers-victims/ | work=CBS News | title=FBI digging up Calif. well looking for more \"Speed Freak Killers\" victims}}</ref>\n| beginyear   = 1984\n| endyear     = 1999\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| states      = [[California]]\n| apprehended = March 17, 1999\n}}\n\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name        = Wesley Shermantine\n| image       = Wesley Shermantine.jpg\n| image_size  = 200px\n| caption     = 2007 San Quentin State Prison mugshot\n| alt         = \n| birthname   = Wesley Howard Shermantine, Jr.\n| alias       = The Speed Freak Killer\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1966|2|24|mf=y}}<ref>California Births, 1905 - 1995, http://www.familytreelegends.com/records/39461?c=search&first=Wesley&last=Shermantine Wesley H. Shermantine</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Linden, California]], U.S.\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| cause       = \n| conviction  = [[Murder]]\n| sentence    = [[Death penalty]]\n| victims     = 4\u201319<ref name=\"CBS News\">{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-201_162-57562673/fbi-digging-up-calif-well-looking-for-more-speed-freak-killers-victims/ | work=CBS News | title=FBI digging up Calif. well looking for more \"Speed Freak Killers\" victims}}</ref> \n| beginyear   = 1984\n| endyear     = 1999\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| states      = [[California]], [[Utah]]\n| apprehended = March 17, 1999\n}}\n\nThe '''Speed Freak Killers''' is the name given to [[serial killer]] duo '''Loren Herzog''' and '''Wesley Shermantine''', together initially convicted of four murders \u2014 three jointly \u2014 and suspected in the deaths of as many as 72 people in and around [[San Joaquin County, California]]. They received the \"speed freak\" moniker due to their [[methamphetamine]] abuse.\n\nHerzog committed suicide in 2012. {{As of|2016}} Shermantine remains on [[death row]] in [[San Quentin State Prison]], in [[San Quentin, California]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Map by 'Speed Freak Killer' Wesley Shermantine leads cops to 300 human bones |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/map-by-speed-freak-killer-wesley-shermantine-leads-cops-to-300-human-bones/ |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=CBSNews.com |date=February 13, 2012 |access-date=October 7, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-serialkiller-20120213,0,2221324.story |url-status=dead |work=Los Angeles Times |first=Diana |last=Marcum |title='Speed Freak' killer's disclosures bring both peace and turmoil |date=February 13, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213212726/http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-serialkiller-20120213,0,2221324.story |archivedate=February 13, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nHerzog and Shermantine grew up as childhood friends in the town of [[Linden, California]]. The citizens of Linden, a small town with fewer than 2,000 people, 95 miles east of [[San Francisco]], were long aware of the duo's reputation as methamphetamine users. They were regulars at the Linden Inn, a bar owned by the father of 25-year-old Cyndi Vanderheiden of [[Clements, California]]. Vanderheiden went missing after leaving the Linden Inn with Herzog and Shermantine on November 14, 1998.\n\nInvestigation into Vanderheiden's disappearance was ongoing into 1999, and Shermantine was the prime suspect.  In mid-January 1999, Shermantine's car was repossessed, and was subsequently searched by the [[San Joaquin County, California|San Joaquin]] Sheriff's Department. Blood identified as being from Cyndi Vanderheiden was discovered in the car, and while [[DNA]] test results were being confirmed, the sheriff's department focused on Loren Herzog, Shermantine's friend and suspected accomplice. He was extensively questioned.\n\nHerzog described when Shermantine shot a hunter they ran into while they were on vacation in Utah in 1994. Utah police confirmed that a hunter was shot to death, but his murder was still classified as unsolved. Herzog also said Shermantine was responsible for killing Henry Howell, who was found parked off the road on Highway 88 in Alpine County with his teeth and head bashed in.  Herzog said he and Shermantine passed Howell parked on the highway and Shermantine stopped, grabbed Howell's shotgun, killed him, and stole what little money he had. Additionally, Herzog gave specific details about how Shermantine killed Robin Armtrout.\n\nHerzog and Shermantine both were arrested by the [[San Joaquin County Sheriff's Department]] and charged with several counts of murder each in March 1999.\n\n== 2001 convictions ==\nIn 2001, a jury found Shermantine guilty of four murders: those of Vanderheiden, Howard King and Paul Cavanaugh&nbsp;\u2013 each shot dead in his car in 1984, and 16-year-old Chevelle \"Chevy\" Wheeler, who disappeared in 1985 from [[Franklin High School (Stockton, California)|Franklin High School]] in [[Stockton, California|Stockton]] after telling friends she was leaving school to go with Shermantine to his family's cabin in [[San Andreas, California|San Andreas]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-504083_162-57379366-504083/speed-freak-killers-update-search-for-victims-remains-reaches-bottom-of-calif-well/ | work=CBS News | title='Speed Freak Killers' Update: Search for victims' remains reaches bottom of Calif. well}}</ref> Shermantine was sentenced to death and is on death row at [[San Quentin State Prison]].\n\nHerzog was charged with five counts of murder in 1999: that of Cyndi Vanderheiden, Henry Howell, Paul Raymond Cavanaugh, Howard Michael King III, and Roberta \"Robin\" Ray Armtrout.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Four additional murder counts filed against Loren Herzog|url = http://www.lodinews.com/news/article_71ee4b7c-379c-11e4-9987-001a4bcf887a.html|website = Lodinews.com|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref> In his 2001 trial, a jury found him guilty on three murder counts (Vanderheiden, Cavanaugh, and King), the lesser charge of accessory to murder in the Howell count, and [[Acquittal|acquitted]] him on the Armtrout count.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Jury finds Herzog guilty|url = http://www.recordnet.com/article/20011024/A_NEWS/310249967|website = recordnet.com|access-date = February 20, 2016|first = Linda Hughes-Kirchubel Record Staff|last = Writer}}</ref> Herzog was given a 78-year sentence.\n\n== Appeals and overturned convictions ==\nAn appeals court overturned all of Herzog's convictions in August 2004, after ruling that three of Herzog's four confessions were coerced.<ref name=\"lodinews.com\">{{Cite web|title = Convicted killer Loren Herzog commits suicide|url = http://www.lodinews.com/news/article_64587e42-4122-11e1-b68e-001871e3ce6c.html|website = Lodinews.com|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref> In the case of the fourth, that of Cyndi Vanderheiden, a retrial was ordered. This retrial never took place. Rather, a plea bargain was reached, where Herzog pleaded guilty to voluntary manslaughter and furnishing amphetamine in the Vanderheiden case, and to being an accessory to murder in the Cavanaugh, King, and Howell cases. Accordingly, Herzog's sentence was reduced to 14 years, with credit for six years served.<ref name=\"lodinews.com\"/> With credit off his sentence for good behavior, Herzog served 11 years in prison and was in a position where he was to be paroled by 2010.\n\nOpposition to the inevitability of Herzog's parole was extremely vocal, especially from victims' families.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Paroled killer Loren Herzog found hanged in his trailer at prison|url = http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/01/loren-herzog-hanged-trailer.html|website = LA Times Blogs - L.A. NOW|date = January 17, 2012|access-date = February 20, 2016|language = en-US}}</ref> That no California county wanted to take him for parole led the California Department of Corrections to parole him to a trailer stationed outside the front gate of the [[High Desert State Prison (California)|High Desert State Prison]] in [[Susanville, California]] in Lassen County in September 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Lassen County loses Herzog parole appeal|url = http://www.recordnet.com/article/20120314/A_NEWS/203140323|website = recordnet.com|access-date = February 20, 2016|first = Scott|last = Smith}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Loren Herzog, Half of \"Speed Freak Killers\" Duo, to be Freed on Parole|url = http://www.cbsnews.com/news/loren-herzog-half-of-speed-freak-killers-duo-to-be-freed-on-parole/|website = www.cbsnews.com|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHerzog committed suicide in January 2012, hanging himself inside his trailer.<ref name=\":0\" /> He did so shortly after [[bounty hunter]] [[Leonard Padilla]] informed Herzog that Shermantine was planning to disclose the location of a well and two other locations where the duo buried their victims. Previously, none of their victims' bodies had been found. Both men maintained that the other did the killing in all cases.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/18/us/serial-killers-graveyard-opens-california-towns-wounds.html | work=The New York Times | first=Malia | last=Wollan | title=Serial Killers' Graveyard Opens California Town's Wounds | date=February 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Discovery of victims' remains==\n\n=== Linden, California well ===\nIn February 2010, while Wesley Shermantine waited on death row, his sister Barbara received letters from him identifying the locations of victims in an abandoned well on Flood Road, near [[Linden, California]]. She turned these letters over to the San Joaquin County Sheriff's Department. The Sheriff's Department followed up on the lead, but in an interview with the property owner, the owner stated that the wells in question were sealed before the victims disappeared. No further action was taken at that time.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Speed Freak Killer's Sister Says Police 'Dropped The Ball' On Her Tips|url = http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2012/10/26/speed-freak-killers-sister-nothing-is-getting-done/|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMore came out in February 2012, based on the promise bounty hunter Leonard Padilla made to Shermantine to pay $33,000 for information.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = Bodies of murder victims found after their killer draws maps for bounty hunter from his death row cell|url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2099654/Wesley-Shermantine-Bodies-murder-victims-killer-draws-maps-death-row-cell.html|website = Mail Online|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref> A map drawn by Shermantine and additional information given again led authorities to the same Linden, California well site he mentioned in 2010. More than 1,000 human bone fragments were recovered. The bones were to be tested by the [[California Department of Justice]] for [[DNA profiling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2012/02/17/speed-freak-killer-speaks-out-in-letter-search-enters-2nd-week/|title='Speed Freak Killer' Speaks Out In Letter, Search Enters 2nd Week|work=cbslocal.com|accessdate=December 12, 2014}}</ref> In March 2012, the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]]'s Evidence Recovery Team was asked to assist with the overall investigation, in part because of how the excavation of the Linden well was handled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2012/03/02/breaking-fbi-now-assisting-in-search-for-victims-of-speed-freak-killers/|title=FBI Asked To Assist In Search For Victims Of 'Speed Freak Killers' \u00ab CBS Sacramento|work=cbslocal.com|accessdate=December 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe identity of the remains recovered in the well were announced to the public on March 30, 2012. They were those of two Stockton, California teens missing since the mid-1980s: Kimberly Ann Billy, 19, who disappeared December 11, 1984 and Joann Hobson, 16, who disappeared August 29, 1985. The remains of an additional victim as well as an unidentified fetus were found in the well.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Two Victims From Linden Well Identified In 'Speed Freak Killers' Case|url = http://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2012/03/30/two-victims-from-linden-well-identified-in-speed-freak-killers-case/|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Former Shermantine property ===\nTwo separate burial sites in [[Calaveras County, California]] were also investigated in February 2012 based on a letter Shermantine wrote to Padilla that detailed possible locations of victims.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|title=Coverage Of Shermantine Property Search|url=http://www.kcra.com/slideshow/news/30508345/detail.html|work=KCRA 3|publisher=KCRA-TV|accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref> Shermantine indicated sites nearby property formerly owned by Shermantine's parents.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\"/> Bodies from these two sites were recovered and identified as those of Chevelle \"Chevy\" Wheeler and Cyndi Vanderheiden.\n\n=== September 2012 burial sites ===\nShermantine was briefly released from death row into police custody in September 2012, to lead authorities to four additional abandoned wells where he stated more victim remains would be found, all near the town of Linden, done because he was paid $28,000 by Leonard Padilla.<ref>{{Cite web|title = 'Speed Freak Killer' on death row leads police to remains of victims he murdered decades ago|url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2197327/Wesley-Shermantine-Speed-Freak-Killer-leads-police-remains-victims-murdered-decades-ago.html|website = Mail Online|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref> In early January 2013 the FBI began excavation of a well site, which they hoped would yield more victims' remains.<ref name=\"CBS News\">{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-201_162-57562673/fbi-digging-up-calif-well-looking-for-more-speed-freak-killers-victims/ | work=CBS News | title=FBI digging up Calif. well looking for more \"Speed Freak Killers\" victims}}</ref> Shermantine declined to speak further to authorities. On February 22, 2013, the FBI announced that it had ended the search for victims based on Shermantine's information. Two sites he had indicated had turned up nothing, and \"other directions from him were misguided\".<ref>{{Cite web|title = Search For Victims Of 'Speed Freak Killers' At An End|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/02/22/speed-freak-killers-victim-search-ends-fbi_n_2741017.html|website = The Huffington Post|access-date = February 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShermantine also claimed to know the locations in the [[Lake County, California#National protected areas|Cow Mountain Recreation Area]] of bodies of victims killed by other death row inmates. [[Lake County, California|Lake County]] sheriffs were skeptical that any bodies could be successfully recovered in the large park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/crime-courts/ci_21154679/speed-freak-killer-hints-at-14-bodies-near|title='Speed freak killer' hints at 14 bodies near Clear Lake|work=mercurynews.com|accessdate=December 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Allegations of investigation-hampering==\nSince 2012, several victims' families and elected officials have alleged that the San Joaquin County Sheriff's Office (SJCSO) interfered with and deliberately hampered the continued search for additional possible victims of the \"Speed Freak Killers\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2015/03/14/speed-freak-killers-case-retired-fbi-agent-alleges-san-joaquin-sheriffs-office-sabotaged-crime-scene/|title=Speed Freak Killers case: Retired FBI agent alleges San Joaquin Sheriff's Office sabotaged crime scene|date=March 14, 2015|work=The Mercury News|access-date=October 8, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\nIn 2010, Shermantine wrote a letter to [[California State Senate|California State Senator]] [[Cathleen Galgiani]]\u2014whose cousin, 19-year-old Dena McHan, disappeared in 1981\u2014revealing the locations of the remains of additional victims.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.lodinews.com/news/article_6e77031e-c69c-11e4-a329-cf3a23ed6e47.html?mode=jqm|title=State Sen. Cathleen Galgiani: 'Speed Freak Killers' records deleted|work=Lodinews.com|access-date=October 7, 2018}}</ref> In 2012, Galgiani sponsored the use of taxpayer funds to search for additional victims of the pair, and sought to simplify protocol granting incarcerated persons like Shermantine permission to participate in search excursions.<ref name=\":4\" /> Galgiani turned the letter over to law enforcement and later alleged that missing persons records related to the \"Speed Freak Killers\" case had been deleted, hampering further investigation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sfgate.com/crime/article/Claim-Speed-Freak-Killers-investigators-impeded-6125947.php|title=Speed Freak Killers investigators stymied kidnap probe, suit says|date=March 10, 2015|work=SFGate|access-date=October 8, 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn 2014, the mother of a missing woman filed suit against the SJCSO for mishandling the remains found in the Linden well.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-speed-freak-killers-case-lands-in-federal-court-2014jan10-story.html|title=Mom says county 'pulverized' Calif. girl's remains|last=Press|first=SCOTT SMITH Associated|work=sandiegouniontribune.com|access-date=October 8, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2015, a retired FBI agent corroborated her claims, alleging that the SJCSO deliberately used a backhoe to dig up remains, mangling them to prevent identification, so that the absence of certain files would not be discovered.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 2018, the Sheriff-elect of San Joaquin County announced that the \"Speed Freak Killers\" case would be re-opened.<ref>{{Citation|last=Meza|first=Melinda|title=Sheriff-elect reopens Speed-Freak killers case in San Joaquin County|url=https://www.kcra.com/article/sheriff-elect-reopens-speed-freak-killers-case-in-san-joaquin-county/23015783|language=en|access-date=October 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==In popular media ==\nThis case was featured on episode 178 of the series ''[[American Justice]]'', \"Vanished\", which first aired September 4, 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|title = American Justice|url = http://www.tv.com/shows/american-justice/episodes/|website = TV.com|access-date = February 20, 2016|last = TV.com}}</ref> With the episode's 2002 production date, newer details relating to this case were not a part of the program. Two of the victims' families (the Wheelers and Vanderheidens) did not yet know where their daughters' bodies were, and Herzog was (still) serving a 78-year sentence.\n\nThe story was covered on the 2015 episode [[On the Case with Paula Zahn#ep145|\u201cWhere Evil Lies\u201d]], on the crime documentary series ''[[On the Case with Paula Zahn]]''. The episode included updates on Herzog\u2019s release and suicide, and the discovery of victims\u2019 remains, including Wheeler and Vanderheiden&mdash;with comments from Wheeler\u2018s and Vanderheiden\u2019s families.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of serial killers in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/serial_killers/partners/speed-freak-killers/an-outraged-community.html \"The Speed Freak Killers\", extensive reportage by Gary C. King, TruTV site]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Speed Freak Killers}}\n[[Category:American serial killers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by California]]\n[[Category:2012 in California]]\n[[Category:2001 in California]]\n[[Category:People from Linden, California]]\n[[Category:Methamphetamine in the United States]]\n[[Category:Criminal duos]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n", "name_user": "99.73.39.166", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eIn popular media:add current postcast to media section)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Speed_Freak_Killers"}
